{"title_page": "Battle pass", "text_new": "{{short description|Type of video game monetization}}\n{{about||the American Revolutionary War site in New York|Battle Pass|the Battle Pass Scenic Byway|Wyoming Highway 70}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n[[File:Battle pass fortnite.png|thumb|right|An example of a Battle pass screen from the game ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'', showing its two-tier, multi-level reward system.]]\nIn the video game industry, a '''battle pass''' is a type of [[video game monetization|monetization approach]] that provides additional content for a game usually through a tiered system, rewarding the player with in-game items by playing the game and completing specific challenges. Inspired by the [[season pass]] ticketing system and originating with ''[[Dota 2]]'' in 2013, the battle pass model gained more use as an alternative to [[Games as a service|subscription fees]] and [[loot box]]es beginning in the late 2010s.\n\n==Concept==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Battle pass fortnite.png|thumb|right|''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' features a dual-track battle pass. The \"free\" track (''top'') is free to all players but offers fewer rewards compared to the \"premium\" track (''bottom''), which requires seasonal payment via microtransactions.]] -->\nWithin a video game, a battle pass may be offered free to a player, or may require the player to purchase it through microtransactions. Once obtained, the battle pass presents the player with a number of reward tiers; by earning enough [[Experience point|experience]] to complete the tier, the player gains the rewards offered at that tier. These rewards are typically cosmetic in nature, such as character and weapon customization options (also known as \"skins\"), emotes, and other non-gameplay affecting elements. More desirable rewards are provided at higher levels, which offer a way for players to show off these unique customization options to other players as a status symbol.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pocketgamer.co.uk/r/iPhone/Fortnite+Battle+Royale/feature.asp?c=77950 | title = Why Fortnite's monetisation is easy to copy but its success hard to replicate | first = Jon | last = Jordan | date = July 2, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[Pocket Gamer]] }}</ref> Experience is gained through normal gameplay, and often through in-game challenges, while some games offer a way to accelerate progression through a battle pass by using microtransactions.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\">{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/battle-passes-are-replacing-loot-boxes-but-theyre-not-necessarily-a-better-deal/ | title = Battle passes are replacing loot boxes, but they're not necessarily a better deal | first = James | last =Davenport | date = July 5, 2018 | accessdate = July 5, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> In games that offer both free and paid-for battle passes, the free pass may have a very limited number of tiers or offer fewer or less-desirable rewards, but will track progress of the player's progression through the paid-for battle pass, allowing them to buy that battle pass at any time to reap the rewards.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/26/17164364/fortnite-battle-royale-guide-loot-box-battle-pass-shop-save-the-world-mode-v-bucks-price-money  | title = Fortnite loot box and Battle Pass beginner\u2019s guide | first=  Chris | last =Carter | date =March 26, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\nBattle passes and the rewards contained are only available for a limited time, most commonly a few months, after which a new season battle pass with a new set of rewards are available to be acquired.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\"/> Battle passes may be called different terms depending on the game. For example, ''[[Rocket League]]'' and ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' offers a \"Rocket Pass\" and \"Survivor Pass\" respectively.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2018/gaming/features/rocket-league-rocket-pass-1202850769/ | title = \u2018Rocket League\u2019 Director Talks Rocket Pass, Loot Boxes, Bonuses and Penalties | first = Steven | last = Wright | date = June 19, 2018 | accessdate = June 19, 2018 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Knezevic |first1=Kevin |title=PUBG's Fortnite-Style Event Pass Available Today With New Update |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pubgs-fortnite-style-event-pass-available-today-wi/1100-6459915/ |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOne of the first known examples of a battle pass concept was seen in [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]'s ''[[Dota 2]]'' during an event that surrounded [[The International 2013]], the annual [[esports]] tournament for the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Van Allen |first1=Eric |title=How Exactly Does Dota 2 Come Up With Over $20 Million In Prizes For Its Biggest Event? |url=https://compete.kotaku.com/how-exactly-does-dota-2-come-up-with-over-20-million-i-1796879005 |website=Kotaku |accessdate=July 14, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714010129/http://compete.kotaku.com/how-exactly-does-dota-2-come-up-with-over-20-million-i-1796879005 |archivedate=July 14, 2017  }}</ref> Called the \"Compendium\", it provided unique in-game content and other features for those players that purchased it, with 25% of all revenue made from it going towards the prize pool for the event.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/battle-passes-are-so-hot-right-now-1827026722 | title = Battle Passes Are So Hot Right Now | first = Cecilia | last = D'Anastasio | date = June 21, 2018 | accessdate = June 21, 2018 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref> In 2016, Valve included the Compendium into the larger International Battle Pass, and later introduced a monthly form of one with their [[Dota Plus]] subscription feature in 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/the-winter-battle-pass-is-valves-best-dota-2-event-yet/ | title = The Winter Battle Pass is Valve's best Dota 2 event yet | first = Chris | last = Thursten | date = January 26, 2016 | accessdate = June 19, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pereira|first1=Chris|title=Valve Overhauls Dota 2 Battle Pass With Subscription-Based Dota Plus|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/valve-overhauls-dota-2-battle-pass-with-subscripti/1100-6457332/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> Valve also added \"campaign passes\" to ''[[Team Fortress 2]]'' with special events in 2015. The campaign pass gave the player that purchased it a number of goals to complete during the event to receive unique customization options.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/team-fortress-2/team-fortress-2s-gun-mettle-update-adds-csgo-like-weapon-skins-and-campaigns | title = Team Fortress 2\u2019s Gun Mettle update adds CS:GO like weapon skins and campaigns | first = Nick  |last =Wilson | date = July 2, 2015 | accessdate = January 24, 2019 | work = [[PCGamesN]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.shacknews.com/article/101778/heres-everything-featured-in-the-team-fortress-2-jungle-inferno-update | title = Here's Everything Featured in the Team Fortress 2 'Jungle Inferno' Update | first=  Ozzie | last= Meija | date = January 24, 2019 | accessdate = January 24, 2019 | work = [[Shacknews]] }}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of these passes grew significantly in 2018 with the use in [[Epic Games]]'s ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''. Its runaway success on a scale rarely seen before drew great interest towards its monetization methods.  The free-to-play game adopted a \"season\"-driven release schedule, each season lasting 10 weeks, during which a new set of cosmetic items and emotes were offered. The newly coined \"Battle Pass\" was added starting in its second season, during a time when the game was seeing a large growth in its player base and has been used by the game since.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/12/15/fortnite-battle-royale-gets-dota-2-style-battle-pass-loads-of-new-items/ | title = Fortnite Battle Royale gets Dota 2-style Battle Pass, loads of new items | first = Sherif | last = Saed | date = December 15, 2017 | accessdate = July 14, 2018 | work = [[VG247]] }}</ref> Battle passes are purchased through an in-game currency called V-bucks, which either must be purchased with real-world funds via microtransactions, or earned via ''[[Fortnite: Save the World]]''. Analyst [[Michael Pachter]] estimated that on the first day of the third season, in February 2018, Epic sold more than five million battle passes, generating over {{USD|50 million}} in revenue in a single day.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-05-25-fortnite-sold-5-million-battle-passes-on-the-first-day-of-season-3 | title = Fortnite sold 5 million battle passes on the first day of Season 3 | first = Rebekah | last =Valentine | date =May 25, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref> With expansion of ''Fortnite'' to mobile devices in March 2018, revenue estimates from the game were in the hundreds of millions of dollars per month in the following months, primarily from battle pass sales.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnet.com/news/fortnite-made-almost-300-million-in-april-shows-no-signs-of-slowing-down/ | title = Fortnite tallied almost $300 million in April, with no signs of slowing down | first=  Jason | last = Parker | date = May 24, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[CNet]] }}</ref>\n\nAt the same time as ''Fortnite'' was becoming a success, the [[video game industry]] had been dealing with the issue of [[loot box]]es, another monetization scheme where players spend funds to open boxes containing a random assortment of in-game items. In the late 2010s, loot boxes faced scrutiny from several government-related groups, believing they encouraged [[gambling]], particularly for young players. Battle passes were then seen as a preferable option to loot boxes, as players would be able to see all the rewards they could earn, even if they needed to spend a great deal of time completing all the tiers, assuring players continued to play the game. Further, by offering the means for players to buy into completing tiers, publishers could also see additional revenue.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\" />\n\nCoupled with the success of ''Fortnite''{{'s}} battle pass approach and exhaustion over loot box controversies, other publishers started to evaluate battle pass use, with gaming journalists theorizing that games which formerly relied on loot boxes or worked [[games as a service|as a service]] could begin to offer battle passes as a replacement.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/fortnite/2018/5/21/17376178/fortnite-season-4-battle-pass-skins-loot-boxes | title = What Fortnite\u2019s Battle Pass gets right | first =Clayton | last = Ashley | date = May 21, 2018 | accessdate = June 19, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Video game monetization}}\n\n[[Category:Business models]]\n[[Category:Video game terminology]]\n[[Category:Video game distribution]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 2010s]]\n[[Category:Video games containing battle passes| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{about||the American Revolutionary War site in New York|Battle Pass|the Battle Pass Scenic Byway|Wyoming Highway 70}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2018}}\n[[File:Battle pass fortnite.png|thumb|right|An example of a Battle pass screen from the game ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'', showing its two-tier, multi-level reward system.]]\nIn the video game industry, a '''battle pass''' is a type of [[video game monetization|monetization approach]] that provides additional content for a game usually through a tiered system, rewarding the player with in-game items by playing the game and completing specific challenges. Inspired by the [[season pass]] ticketing system and originating with ''[[Dota 2]]'' in 2013, the battle pass model gained more use as an alternative to [[Games as a service|subscription fees]] and [[loot box]]es beginning in the late 2010s.\n\n==Concept==\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Battle pass fortnite.png|thumb|right|''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]'' features a dual-track battle pass. The \"free\" track (''top'') is free to all players but offers fewer rewards compared to the \"premium\" track (''bottom''), which requires seasonal payment via microtransactions.]] -->\nWithin a video game, a battle pass may be offered free to a player, or may require the player to purchase it through microtransactions. Once obtained, the battle pass presents the player with a number of reward tiers; by earning enough [[Experience point|experience]] to complete the tier, the player gains the rewards offered at that tier. These rewards are typically cosmetic in nature, such as character and weapon customization options (also known as \"skins\"), emotes, and other non-gameplay affecting elements. More desirable rewards are provided at higher levels, which offer a way for players to show off these unique customization options to other players as a status symbol.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.pocketgamer.co.uk/r/iPhone/Fortnite+Battle+Royale/feature.asp?c=77950 | title = Why Fortnite's monetisation is easy to copy but its success hard to replicate | first = Jon | last = Jordan | date = July 2, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[Pocket Gamer]] }}</ref> Experience is gained through normal gameplay, and often through in-game challenges, while some games offer a way to accelerate progression through a battle pass by using microtransactions.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\">{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/battle-passes-are-replacing-loot-boxes-but-theyre-not-necessarily-a-better-deal/ | title = Battle passes are replacing loot boxes, but they're not necessarily a better deal | first = James | last =Davenport | date = July 5, 2018 | accessdate = July 5, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref> In games that offer both free and paid-for battle passes, the free pass may have a very limited number of tiers or offer fewer or less-desirable rewards, but will track progress of the player's progression through the paid-for battle pass, allowing them to buy that battle pass at any time to reap the rewards.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\"/><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/2018/3/26/17164364/fortnite-battle-royale-guide-loot-box-battle-pass-shop-save-the-world-mode-v-bucks-price-money  | title = Fortnite loot box and Battle Pass beginner\u2019s guide | first=  Chris | last =Carter | date =March 26, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\nBattle passes and the rewards contained are only available for a limited time, most commonly a few months, after which a new season battle pass with a new set of rewards are available to be acquired.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\"/> Battle passes may be called different terms depending on the game. For example, ''[[Rocket League]]'' and ''[[PlayerUnknown's Battlegrounds]]'' offers a \"Rocket Pass\" and \"Survivor Pass\" respectively.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://variety.com/2018/gaming/features/rocket-league-rocket-pass-1202850769/ | title = \u2018Rocket League\u2019 Director Talks Rocket Pass, Loot Boxes, Bonuses and Penalties | first = Steven | last = Wright | date = June 19, 2018 | accessdate = June 19, 2018 | work = [[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Knezevic |first1=Kevin |title=PUBG's Fortnite-Style Event Pass Available Today With New Update |url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/pubgs-fortnite-style-event-pass-available-today-wi/1100-6459915/ |website=Eurogamer |accessdate=9 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOne of the first known examples of a battle pass concept was seen in [[Valve Corporation|Valve]]'s ''[[Dota 2]]'' during an event that surrounded [[The International 2013]], the annual [[esports]] tournament for the game.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Van Allen |first1=Eric |title=How Exactly Does Dota 2 Come Up With Over $20 Million In Prizes For Its Biggest Event? |url=https://compete.kotaku.com/how-exactly-does-dota-2-come-up-with-over-20-million-i-1796879005 |website=Kotaku |accessdate=July 14, 2017 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714010129/http://compete.kotaku.com/how-exactly-does-dota-2-come-up-with-over-20-million-i-1796879005 |archivedate=July 14, 2017  }}</ref> Called the \"Compendium\", it provided unique in-game content and other features for those players that purchased it, with 25% of all revenue made from it going towards the prize pool for the event.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://kotaku.com/battle-passes-are-so-hot-right-now-1827026722 | title = Battle Passes Are So Hot Right Now | first = Cecilia | last = D'Anastasio | date = June 21, 2018 | accessdate = June 21, 2018 | work = [[Kotaku]] }}</ref> In 2016, Valve included the Compendium into the larger International Battle Pass, and later introduced a monthly form of one with their [[Dota Plus]] subscription feature in 2018.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/the-winter-battle-pass-is-valves-best-dota-2-event-yet/ | title = The Winter Battle Pass is Valve's best Dota 2 event yet | first = Chris | last = Thursten | date = January 26, 2016 | accessdate = June 19, 2018 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Pereira|first1=Chris|title=Valve Overhauls Dota 2 Battle Pass With Subscription-Based Dota Plus|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/valve-overhauls-dota-2-battle-pass-with-subscripti/1100-6457332/|website=GameSpot|accessdate=March 12, 2018}}</ref> Valve also added \"campaign passes\" to ''[[Team Fortress 2]]'' with special events in 2015. The campaign pass gave the player that purchased it a number of goals to complete during the event to receive unique customization options.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamesn.com/team-fortress-2/team-fortress-2s-gun-mettle-update-adds-csgo-like-weapon-skins-and-campaigns | title = Team Fortress 2\u2019s Gun Mettle update adds CS:GO like weapon skins and campaigns | first = Nick  |last =Wilson | date = July 2, 2015 | accessdate = January 24, 2019 | work = [[PCGamesN]] }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.shacknews.com/article/101778/heres-everything-featured-in-the-team-fortress-2-jungle-inferno-update | title = Here's Everything Featured in the Team Fortress 2 'Jungle Inferno' Update | first=  Ozzie | last= Meija | date = January 24, 2019 | accessdate = January 24, 2019 | work = [[Shacknews]] }}</ref>\n\nThe popularity of these passes grew significantly in 2018 with the use in [[Epic Games]]'s ''[[Fortnite Battle Royale]]''. Its runaway success on a scale rarely seen before drew great interest towards its monetization methods.  The free-to-play game adopted a \"season\"-driven release schedule, each season lasting 10 weeks, during which a new set of cosmetic items and emotes were offered. The newly coined \"Battle Pass\" was added starting in its second season, during a time when the game was seeing a large growth in its player base and has been used by the game since.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.vg247.com/2017/12/15/fortnite-battle-royale-gets-dota-2-style-battle-pass-loads-of-new-items/ | title = Fortnite Battle Royale gets Dota 2-style Battle Pass, loads of new items | first = Sherif | last = Saed | date = December 15, 2017 | accessdate = July 14, 2018 | work = [[VG247]] }}</ref> Battle passes are purchased through an in-game currency called V-bucks, which either must be purchased with real-world funds via microtransactions, or earned via ''[[Fortnite: Save the World]]''. Analyst [[Michael Pachter]] estimated that on the first day of the third season, in February 2018, Epic sold more than five million battle passes, generating over {{USD|50 million}} in revenue in a single day.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.gamesindustry.biz/articles/2018-05-25-fortnite-sold-5-million-battle-passes-on-the-first-day-of-season-3 | title = Fortnite sold 5 million battle passes on the first day of Season 3 | first = Rebekah | last =Valentine | date =May 25, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[GamesIndustry.biz]] }}</ref> With expansion of ''Fortnite'' to mobile devices in March 2018, revenue estimates from the game were in the hundreds of millions of dollars per month in the following months, primarily from battle pass sales.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.cnet.com/news/fortnite-made-almost-300-million-in-april-shows-no-signs-of-slowing-down/ | title = Fortnite tallied almost $300 million in April, with no signs of slowing down | first=  Jason | last = Parker | date = May 24, 2018 | accessdate = July 6, 2018 | work = [[CNet]] }}</ref>\n\nAt the same time as ''Fortnite'' was becoming a success, the [[video game industry]] had been dealing with the issue of [[loot box]]es, another monetization scheme where players spend funds to open boxes containing a random assortment of in-game items. In the late 2010s, loot boxes faced scrutiny from several government-related groups, believing they encouraged [[gambling]], particularly for young players. Battle passes were then seen as a preferable option to loot boxes, as players would be able to see all the rewards they could earn, even if they needed to spend a great deal of time completing all the tiers, assuring players continued to play the game. Further, by offering the means for players to buy into completing tiers, publishers could also see additional revenue.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\" />\n\nCoupled with the success of ''Fortnite''{{'s}} battle pass approach and exhaustion over loot box controversies, other publishers started to evaluate battle pass use, with gaming journalists theorizing that games which formerly relied on loot boxes or worked [[games as a service|as a service]] could begin to offer battle passes as a replacement.<ref name=\"pcgamer july2018\" /><ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.polygon.com/fortnite/2018/5/21/17376178/fortnite-season-4-battle-pass-skins-loot-boxes | title = What Fortnite\u2019s Battle Pass gets right | first =Clayton | last = Ashley | date = May 21, 2018 | accessdate = June 19, 2018 | work = [[Polygon (website)|Polygon]] }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Video game monetization}}\n\n[[Category:Business models]]\n[[Category:Video game terminology]]\n[[Category:Video game distribution]]\n[[Category:Words coined in the 2010s]]\n[[Category:Video games containing battle passes| ]]\n", "name_user": "Ayenaee", "label": "safe", "comment": "Importing Wikidatashort description: \"Type of video game monetization\" (Shortdesc helper)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Battle_pass"}
{"title_page": "Castleknock", "text_new": "{{short description|Western suburb of Dublin, Ireland}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Suburb (village core)\n|name                   = Castleknock\n|native_name            = {{Font color|Green|''Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha''}}  \n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|53.374|-6.359|dim:100000_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|O078378}}\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{IRL}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Leinster]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Fingal]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|Council]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Fingal County Council]]\n|subdivision_type4      = D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann\n|subdivision_name4      = [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]]\n|subdivision_type5      = EU Parliament\n|subdivision_name5      = [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]]\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 63\n|area_code_type         = Dialing code\n|area_code              = 01, +353 1\n|postal_code_type       = [[Postal codes in the Republic of Ireland|Postal district(s)]]\n|postal_code            = [[Dublin 15]]\n|population_as_of       = 2011\n|population_urban       = 23,195\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"cso2006\">{{cite web|title=Census 2006 \u2013 Volume 1 \u2013 Population Classified by Area |work=Central Statistics Office Census 2006 Reports |publisher=[[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|Central Statistics Office Ireland]] |date=April 2007 |url=http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607074609/http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf |archivedate=2011-06-07 }}</ref>\n<ref>[https://www.cso.ie/en/media/csoie/census/documents/census2011vol1andprofile1/Table_5.pdf] Census 2011- population classified by area: see two references to Castleknock under Fingal areas.</ref>\n}}\n'''Castleknock''' ({{Irish place name|Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha|Cnucha's Castle}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.ie/~svc/history2.html|title=The Pre-Christian Era|author=|date=|website=www.iol.ie|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>) is an affluent residential outer [[suburb]] of [[Dublin]],<ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/it-can-happen-anywhere-says-neighbour-of-man-killed-in-castleknock-1.1652919</ref> centred on a village, in [[Fingal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It is located {{convert|8|km|0|abbr=on}} west<ref>Geographic co-ordinates from GPO to Post Office in Castleknock: from 53.349501,-6.260287 to 53.373024,-6.362393</ref> of the centre of Dublin.\n\nCastleknock also refers to a [[townland]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Castleknock townland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17267.aspx |title=Castleknock townland &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>, [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Castleknock civil parish\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/835.aspx |title=Castleknock civil parish &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Castleknock (barony)|barony]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Castleknock barony\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/64.aspx |title=Castleknock barony&#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> of the same name.\n\n==Location and access==\n[[Image:Castleknock Village - geograph.org.uk - 493593.jpg|thumb|left|Castleknock Village at the junction of Castleknock Road and College Road]]\n[[File:Royal Canal at Castleknock - geograph.org.uk - 347930.jpg|thumb|Royal Canal at Castleknock]]\n[[File:Castleknock Railway Station Sept 2012.jpg|thumb|Castleknock railway station]]\nThe neighbourhood is located mostly between the Phoenix Park and the Royal Canal and comprises four historical [[townland]]s: Castleknock, Carpenterstown, Astagob (Castleknock) and Diswellstown.<ref>http://map.geohive.ie/mapviewer.html</ref> The neighbourhood is bordered to the west by the large suburb of [[Blanchardstown]], to the east by the [[Phoenix Park]], to the north by [[Dunsink]] and to the south by the village of [[Chapelizod]] above the [[River Liffey|Liffey]] valley. The suburb is in the [[Dublin 15]] [[List of Dublin postal districts|postal area]].\n\n* The [[Royal Canal]] passes through the area from east to west.\n* The area can be accessed by Junction 6 on The M50 motorway. The [[R147 road (Ireland)|R147]] Navan Road also serves the area.\n* Bus services are provided by \n[[Dublin Bus]]. Route 37 runs from Blanchardstown Town Centre to Wilton Terrace, Baggot Street. Route 38 bus runs from Burlington Rd. towards Damastown and vice versa.\n* [[File:Castleknock Train Station (2018).jpg|thumb|Sign at Castleknock railway station]] The  [[Dublin Suburban Rail]] the Western Suburban Railway Line or Maynooth Line running from [[Dublin Connolly]] to  [[Maynooth]]. [[Castleknock railway station]] opened on 2 July 1990.<ref>{{cite web | title= Castleknock station| work=Railscot - Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf | accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n''\"During the Milesian era Castleknock is named as one of twenty-five places at which Conmhaol of the race of Eber, while holding the sovereignty of Ireland, defeated in battle the descendants of Eremon,' and a Celtic writer mentions that Castleknock was sometimes known as duma meic Eremon, or the duma of the sons of Eremon.' The mention of a duma shows that there was at a very early time an eminence of note at Castleknock ; the duma may have been, Mr. Westropp observes, used for purposes of residence, sepulchre, or outlook, or, as in the case of Duma Selga, for all three.\"''\n\n''In a poem relating to the earliest centuries after Christ the origin of the name Cnucha is connected with Conn of the Hundred Battles, and the name is said to have been borne by his foster-mother: \u2014 \n:''The nurse of Conn who loved this strip of land\n:Was Cnucha of the comely head;\n:She dwelt on the dun with him\n:In the reign of Conn of the Hundred Fights.\n:Cnucha, the daughter of Concadh Cas,\n:From the land of Luimncach broad and green,\n:Died yonder in that house\n:To the horror of the Gaels.\n:The woman was buried, a grief it was.\n:In the very middle of the hill ;\n:So that from that on Cnucha\n:Is its name until the judgment.''<ref>A HISTORY OF COUNTY DUBLIN: FRANCIS ELRINGTON BALL  https://archive.org/stream/historyofcountyd06ball/historyofcountyd06ball_djvu.txt</ref>\n\n===Feudal period===\nIn 1167 Roderick O\u2019Connor, [[King of Connacht]], encamped at Castleknock with his forces and engaged the Danish residents in his pay. He led a large army to Dublin where he was solemnly inaugurated as [[High King of Ireland]]. By 1177, a feudal [[Castleknock (barony)|barony of Castleknock]] was created out of the [[Lordship of Meath]] by [[Hugh de Lacy, Lord of Meath]] who granted it to Hugh Tyrrel. It was held for three and a half knight's fees, owed to the superior Lord of Fingal. The title and lands of Castleknock were held by the Tyrell family until 1370 when Hugh Tyrell and his wife died of the Plague. It passed by inheritance to the Burnell family. The first Baron, [[Hugh Tyrrel]], gave lands in the barony at Kilmainham to the [[Venerable Order of St John|Knights of St. John]] who continue in the area today in the form of [[St. John Ambulance Brigade of Ireland|St. John Ambulance]]. Later, [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parishes]], based on the boundaries of the [[Ecclesiastical parish]]es of the [[Established church]] were used to sub-divide the barony.\n\nIn 1185, Richard de Tyrell, son of the first Baron of Castleknock, gave a grant to the Benedictine Monks of the Abbey of Little Malvern, Worcestershire, to endow a religious house at Castleknock in honour of Saint Brigid<ref>Harris's Table in Ware-Harris, Antiquitie, 1745 and Mervyn Archdall, Monasticon Hibernicum, 1786</ref>. Later they built a chapel, the White Chapel at Coolmine, which served the parish of Clonsilla. In 1219 The great tithes of the parish were appropriated by Archbishop Henry de Londres to the Priory of Malvern on condition that they should add five monks to their number. In 1225 the monks granted half of the tithes of the manor of Castleknock to the use of St Patrick\u2019s Cathedral, renouncing to the Archbishop all rights to the vicarage and its small tithes and oblations. In 1226 the first Prebendary of Castleknock, Richard De Gnouessale, was appointed. However, by 1468 the Church and lands at Castleknock were transferred to the ownership of the Abbey of St. Mary near Dublin. Following the [[English Reformation]] and the [[dissolution of the monasteries]] under [[Henry VIII of England]], the Priory at Castleknock was destroyed and in 1609 a church was built on the site for the use of the [[Church of Ireland]]. The foundation stone of the church, which is in use today, still on the site of the Abbey, was laid in 1803.<ref>Church of Ireland - history http://www.castleknock.dublin.anglican.org/history/history.html</ref> The spire was added in 1864 by friends of the late [[James Hans Hamilton]] as a memorial to the 1st Baron HolmPatrick of Abbottown and [[Member of Parliament|MP]]for the County of Dublin. \n\nIn the townland of Diswellstown there is a historic \"rag well\" - a holy well near which rags were left. Although it still flows, it was \"buried\" by the County Council, and its site is now marked by a carved flagstone. Nearby the Diswellstown Stream, which rises near Castleknock village, flows west and then turns sharply south, taking in a streamlet from Carpenterstown, before running down to the Liffey in a narrow steep valley.\n\nCastleknock eventually came to be divided among a number of important families and their country estates. These included the Guinness at [[Farmleigh]], and Knockmaroon, the Laidlaws at Abbey Lodge, the Godleys at Oatlands, and the Brookes at Sommerton House.<ref>https://reynoldshistorycastleknockblog.wordpress.com/2018/04/27/knockmaroon-estate-local-history-castleknock/</ref>\n\nThe Earl of Iveagh's principle seat was at [[Farmleigh House]] until 1999 when it was purchased by the Government of Ireland. It was restored and converted into a State Guest House and opened to the public in 2001. Although they left Farmleigh in 1999, the Guinness family are still present in Castleknock at Knockmaroon House which is located on Carpenterstown Road and the seat of [[Lord Moyne]], The [[Brooke Baronets]] lived st Sommerton House until they sold it in 1911 to the Laidlaw family who were resident at Sommerton and Abbey Lodge until the 1980s<ref>https://reynoldshistorycastleknockblog.wordpress.com/tag/laidlaw-family/</ref>.\n\n===Civil parish===\nWithin the civil parish of Castleknock, there are 22 [[townlands]] per the table below. Like all civil parishes in Ireland, this civil parish is derived from, and co-extensive with, a pre-existing parish of the [[Church of Ireland]]. In 1773, an act of council united the parish with the curacies of Clonsilla and Mulhuddart. In 1837, Lewis' directory reported that the living (of the ecclesiastical parish) was a vicarage in the diocese of [[Archdiocese of Dublin|Dublin]] which was: \"... endowed with a portion of the great tithes, and united to the prebend of Castleknock and the rectory of Clonsillagh and curacy of Mullahidart, with cure of souls: it is in the patronage of the Bishop.\".<ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/irl/DUB/Castleknock Lewis,] \"Topographical Dictionary of Ireland\", 1837</ref> The two churches noted by Lewis in the vicarial union, one at Castleknock, the other at Clonsilla, are extant and in use by the Church of Ireland community. The former was rebuilt by a loan of \u00a31000 from the [[Board of First Fruits]] and large subscriptions, in 1810. In 1831, the population of the parish, including Blanchardstown was 4251 people of which 3409 were Catholic.<ref>''The History of the County of Dublin'', John D'Alton, 1838</ref>\n \nThe core of the parish is centred on the townland and village of the same name. The townland at the northern extremity is Huntstown, not to be confused with [[Huntstown and Littlepace]] in the neighbouring parish of [[Clonsilla]].To the south, it is bounded by the [[River Liffey]] and the [[Phoenix Park]]. To the west, it is bounded by [[Coolmine railway station]] and [[Blanchardstown Shopping Centre]]. To the east lies the 8th lock of the [[Royal Canal]] and the Cabra Gate of the Phoenix Park.\n \nFor convenience, the table below groups the parish's townlands by their location in one of the modern [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|local authority]] areas. Some townlands, however, straddle both areas.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"width:80px\" | Modern Local<br>[[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|Authority Area]]\n! style=\"width:200px\" | Name in Irish\n! style=\"width:200px\" | Name in English\n! style=\"width:40px\" | Acres\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Dublin|Dublin City]]\n|Baile an \u00c1saigh\n|[[Ashtown, Dublin|Ashtown]] <small>(partly)</small>\n|278\n|-\n|Baile Pheil\u00e9id\n|Pelletstown\n|259\n|- \n|An Chabrach\n|[[Cabra, Dublin|Cabra]]\n|457\n|-\n|Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha (cuid de Ph\u00e1irc an Fhionnuisce)\n|Castleknock (part of Phoenix Park)<br><small>(partly)</small>\n|1020<br>(787)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"20\" |[[Fingal]]\n|Baile an Aba\n|[[Abbotstown]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Abbotstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17224.aspx |title=Abbotstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|101\n|- \n|Baile an \u00c1saigh\n|[[Ashtown, Dublin|Ashtown]] <small>(partly)</small><ref group=\"4\" name=\"Ashtown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17263.aspx |title=Ashtown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|278\n|- \n|Baile an Chairpint\u00e9araigh\n|Carpenterstown</small><ref group=\"4\" name=\"Carpenterstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17266.aspx |title=Carpenterstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|166\n|- \n|Baile an D\u00e9anaigh\n|Deanestown</small><ref group=\"4\" name=\"Deanestown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17228.aspx |title=Deanestown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|173\n|- \n|Baile an Diosualaigh\n|Diswellstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Diswellstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17269.aspx |title=Diswellstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|418\n|- \n|Baile an Huntaigh\n|Huntstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Huntstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17230.aspx |title=Huntstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|299\n|- \n|Baile an Ph\u00f3irt\u00e9araigh\n|Porterstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Porterstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17271.aspx |title=Porterstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|219\n|- \n|Baile Bhlains\u00e9ir\n|Blanchardstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Blanchardstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/1412097.aspx |title=Blanchardstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|454\n|- \n|Baile Mhist\u00e9il\n|Mitchelstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Mitchelstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17232.aspx |title=Mitchelstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|154\n|-  \n|Baile Scriobail\n|Scribblestown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Scribblestown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17270.aspx |title=Scribblestown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|272\n|- \n|Baile She\u00e1in\n|Johnstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Johnstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17558.aspx |title=Johnstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n| 67\n|- \n|An Chabrach\n|[[Cabra, Dublin|Cabra]]\n|457\n|- \n|Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha (cuid de Ph\u00e1irc an Fhionnuisce)\n|Castleknock <br>(part of Phoenix Park)<br><small>(partly)</small>\n|1020<br>(787)\n|- \n|Ceapach\n|Cappoge or Cappagh\n|698\n|- \n|Cnoc na gCaorach\n|Sheephill\n|349\n|- \n|An Chorr Dhubh\n|[[Corduff]]\n|353\n|- \n|D\u00fan Sinche\n|[[Dunsink]]\n|423\n|- \n|P\u00e1irc Anna\n|Annfield\n| 19\n|-\n|Snugborough\n|Snugborough\n| 53\n|- \n|Steach Gob\n|Astagob\n| 93\n|-\n|}\n\n==Castleknock today==\n[[File:Arts and Crafts style cottages, Main Street, Castlekock, Dublin 15.jpg|thumb|Arts and Crafts style cottages, Main Street, Castlekmock]]\n[[File:St Bridgets Castleknock 2012.jpg|thumb|\"St. Briget's, Church of Ireland\"]]\n[[File:St Thomas the Apostle.jpg|thumb|\"St Thomas the Apostle\",<br> Laurel Lodge, Castleknock]]\n[[File:Castleknock Catholic Church.jpg|thumb|\"Our Lady Mother of the Church\",<br> Catholic church, Castleknock.]]\n[[File:Stained glass window, St. Thomas Church, Castleknock, Dublin. Ireland.jpg|thumb|Stained glass window, St. Thomas the Apostle, Laurel Lodge]]\n\nThe village is a busy commercial centre with several supermarkets and other retail outlets. There is a post-office and several cafes and restaurants. There are three primary schools in the village, Castleknock National School (Church of Ireland), St. Brigid's Primary School (Roman Catholic), and Castleknock Educate Together (Non-Denominational). Outside the village there is also Scoil Thom\u00e1is Co-educational Primary School in Laurel Lodge district and St. Patrick's Co-educational Primary School in Diswellstown. Castleknock Co-educational Community School (Multi-Denominational) is located on Carpenterstown Road.  Mount Sackville Roman Catholic independent secondary school for girls was founded in 1864 by the Sisters of St. Joseph of Cluny. \n\n\n\n====Community groups====\n* Local First Aid training, event cover and community care in the Castleknock area is provided by [http://www.stjohncastleknock.ie St. John Ambulance Castleknock Combined Division] and the [http://www.orderofmaltaireland.org/index.php/contact/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=197 Order of Malta Castleknock] <ref>[http://www.orderofmaltaireland.org/index.php/contact/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=197] Order of Malta Castleknock</ref>\n* There are a number of residents associations such as \"Riverwood Residents Association\" and \"Carpenterstown Park Residents Association\".<ref>[http://www.communityvoice.ie/pages/CV162/CV162c03.htm Community Voice, ''Carpenterstown residents\u2019 association launch new website.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330075610/http://www.communityvoice.ie/pages/CV162/CV162c03.htm |date=2012-03-30 }}</ref>\n* There is an active Tidy Towns Committee.\n* Castleknock Community Centre,<ref>[http://www.castleknockcommunitycentre.ie] Castleknock Community Centre website.</ref> in the Laurel Lodge area, hosts a range of social, sporting and charitable groups.\n* [http://www.castleknockscouts.ie Castleknock Scout Group], the 175th Castleknock, Dublin Troop, operate in the main village area and the Laurel Lodge and Carpenterstown areas.\n\n=== Religious institutions ===\n[[St. Brigid]] is the patron saint of the village.\n\nIn the [[Church of Ireland]], the church of St. Brigid, cited on the ruins of an ancient monastery, is located in the middle of the village. In the [[Catholic Church]], there are two [[Ecclesiastic parish|parishes]] in the suburb: \"Our Lady Mother of the Church\" which is centred close to the village and [[St Thomas the Apostle parish, Laurel Lodge]].\n  \nBoth St. Brigid's and St. Thomas the Apostle contain windows from the [[Harry Clarke]] Studios. The window in St. Brigid's was commissioned in 1927 by R.F. Brookes of Somerton House, Castleknock, to commemorate members of his family, whereas the Harry Clarke window in St. Thomas the Apostle was donated by the Domincan Order after their convent at D\u00fan Laoghaire closed in 1991. It depicts the Immaculate Conception of Mary.\n\n===Government and representation===\nCastleknock is located in the \"Castleknock ward\" for the purposes of elections to [[Fingal County Council]] and is in the [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)]] and in [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\nFrom {{cite web |url=http://www.logainm.ie/?uiLang=en |title=Irish placenames database |publisher=Department of Community, Rural and Gaeltacht Affairs |work=[[logainm.ie]] |language=English, Irish |accessdate=13 April 2020}}\n:{{reflist |30em|group=4}}\n\nOther:\n<ref name=\"http://www.castleknock.net/\">{{cite web|title=Castleknock Gaa Club|url=http://www.castleknock.net/|website=Castleknock.net|publisher=Web Design Dublin by Webtrade|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2001/en/act/pub/0037/sec0010.html Local Government Act, 2001]\n* [http://www.castleknock.dublin.anglican.org/history/castleknock.html History of Castleknock Church of Ireland]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100218031824/http://www.transport21.ie/Projects/Metro_-_Luas/Metro_-_Luas.html Official \"Transport 21\" site ]\n* [http://www.castleknock.net/ Castleknock Hurling & Football Club ]\n* [http://www.castleknockcollege.ie/ Official Castleknock College website ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090626121538/http://www.mountsackville.ie/index.asp Official Mount Sackville School website ]\n* [http://www.castleknockhotel.com/?gclid=CPeDg4CVq9ACFdXNGwod958A2w Castleknock Hotel & Country Club]\n* [http://www.stpatricksns.ie/ St Patrick's National School, Diswellstown],\n\n{{Dublin residential areas}}\n{{Fingal}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Castleknock|  ]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes of the barony of Castleknock]]\n[[Category:Townlands of Fingal]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Western suburb of Dublin, Ireland}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|settlement_type        = Suburb (village core)\n|name                   = Castleknock\n|native_name            = {{Font color|Green|''Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha''}}  \n|pushpin_map            = Ireland\n|pushpin_label_position = left\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Ireland\n|coordinates            = {{coord|53.374|-6.359|dim:100000_region:IE|display=inline,title}}\n|blank_name_sec1        = Irish Grid Reference\n|blank_info_sec1        = {{iem4ibx|O078378}}\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{IRL}}\n|subdivision_type1      = [[Provinces of Ireland|Province]]\n|subdivision_name1      = [[Leinster]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Ireland|County]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Fingal]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|Council]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Fingal County Council]]\n|subdivision_type4      = D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann\n|subdivision_name4      = [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]]\n|subdivision_type5      = EU Parliament\n|subdivision_name5      = [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]]\n|unit_pref              = Metric\n|elevation_m            = 63\n|area_code_type         = Dialing code\n|area_code              = 01, +353 1\n|postal_code_type       = [[Postal codes in the Republic of Ireland|Postal district(s)]]\n|postal_code            = [[Dublin 15]]\n|population_as_of       = 2011\n|population_urban       = 23,195\n|population_footnotes   = <ref name=\"cso2006\">{{cite web|title=Census 2006 \u2013 Volume 1 \u2013 Population Classified by Area |work=Central Statistics Office Census 2006 Reports |publisher=[[Central Statistics Office (Ireland)|Central Statistics Office Ireland]] |date=April 2007 |url=http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf |format=PDF |accessdate=2011-06-12 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110607074609/http://www.cso.ie/census/documents/census2006_volume_1_pop_classified_by_area.pdf |archivedate=2011-06-07 }}</ref>\n<ref>[https://www.cso.ie/en/media/csoie/census/documents/census2011vol1andprofile1/Table_5.pdf] Census 2011- population classified by area: see two references to Castleknock under Fingal areas.</ref>\n}}\n'''Castleknock''' ({{Irish place name|Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha|Cnucha's Castle}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iol.ie/~svc/history2.html|title=The Pre-Christian Era|author=|date=|website=www.iol.ie|accessdate=13 April 2018}}</ref>) is an affluent residential outer [[suburb]] of [[Dublin]],<ref>https://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/it-can-happen-anywhere-says-neighbour-of-man-killed-in-castleknock-1.1652919</ref> centred on a village, in [[Fingal]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]. It is located {{convert|8|km|0|abbr=on}} west<ref>Geographic co-ordinates from GPO to Post Office in Castleknock: from 53.349501,-6.260287 to 53.373024,-6.362393</ref> of the centre of Dublin.\n\nCastleknock also refers to a [[townland]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Castleknock townland\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17267.aspx |title=Castleknock townland &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref>, [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parish]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Castleknock civil parish\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/835.aspx |title=Castleknock civil parish &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> and [[Castleknock (barony)|barony]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Castleknock barony\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/64.aspx |title=Castleknock barony&#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=13 April 2020}}</ref> of the same name.\n\n==Location and access==\n[[Image:Castleknock Village - geograph.org.uk - 493593.jpg|thumb|left|Castleknock Village at the junction of Castleknock Road and College Road]]\n[[File:Royal Canal at Castleknock - geograph.org.uk - 347930.jpg|thumb|Royal Canal at Castleknock]]\n[[File:Castleknock Railway Station Sept 2012.jpg|thumb|Castleknock railway station]]\nThe neighbourhood is located mostly between the Phoenix Park and the Royal Canal and comprises four historical [[townland]]s: Castleknock, Carpenterstown, Astagob (Castleknock) and Diswellstown.<ref>http://map.geohive.ie/mapviewer.html</ref> The neighbourhood is bordered to the west by the large suburb of [[Blanchardstown]], to the east by the [[Phoenix Park]], to the north by [[Dunsink]] and to the south by the village of [[Chapelizod]] above the [[River Liffey|Liffey]] valley. The suburb is in the [[Dublin 15]] [[List of Dublin postal districts|postal area]].\n\n* The [[Royal Canal]] passes through the area from east to west.\n* The area can be accessed by Junction 6 on The M50 motorway. The [[R147 road (Ireland)|R147]] Navan Road also serves the area.\n* Bus services are provided by \n[[Dublin Bus]]. Route 37 runs from Blanchardstown Town Centre to Wilton Terrace, Baggot Street. Route 38 bus runs from Burlington Rd. towards Damastown and vice versa.\n* [[File:Castleknock Train Station (2018).jpg|thumb|Sign at Castleknock railway station]] The  [[Dublin Suburban Rail]] the Western Suburban Railway Line or Maynooth Line running from [[Dublin Connolly]] to  [[Maynooth]]. [[Castleknock railway station]] opened on 2 July 1990.<ref>{{cite web | title= Castleknock station| work=Railscot - Irish Railways | url=http://www.railscot.co.uk/Ireland/Irish_railways.pdf | accessdate=2007-08-31}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n\n''\"During the Milesian era Castleknock is named as one of twenty-five places at which Conmhaol of the race of Eber, while holding the sovereignty of Ireland, defeated in battle the descendants of Eremon,' and a Celtic writer mentions that Castleknock was sometimes known as duma meic Eremon, or the duma of the sons of Eremon.' The mention of a duma shows that there was at a very early time an eminence of note at Castleknock ; the duma may have been, Mr. Westropp observes, used for purposes of residence, sepulchre, or outlook, or, as in the case of Duma Selga, for all three.\"''\n\n''In a poem relating to the earliest centuries after Christ the origin of the name Cnucha is connected with Conn of the Hundred Battles, and the name is said to have been borne by his foster-mother: \u2014 \n:''The nurse of Conn who loved this strip of land\n:Was Cnucha of the comely head;\n:She dwelt on the dun with him\n:In the reign of Conn of the Hundred Fights.\n:Cnucha, the daughter of Concadh Cas,\n:From the land of Luimncach broad and green,\n:Died yonder in that house\n:To the horror of the Gaels.\n:The woman was buried, a grief it was.\n:In the very middle of the hill ;\n:So that from that on Cnucha\n:Is its name until the judgment.''<ref>A HISTORY OF COUNTY DUBLIN: FRANCIS ELRINGTON BALL  https://archive.org/stream/historyofcountyd06ball/historyofcountyd06ball_djvu.txt</ref>\n\n===Feudal period===\nIn 1167 Roderick O\u2019Connor, [[King of Connacht]], encamped at Castleknock with his forces and engaged the Danish residents in his pay. He led a large army to Dublin where he was solemnly inaugurated as [[High King of Ireland]]. By 1177, a feudal [[Castleknock (barony)|barony of Castleknock]] was created out of the [[Lordship of Meath]] by [[Hugh de Lacy, Lord of Meath]] who granted it to Hugh Tyrrel. It was held for three and a half knight's fees, owed to the superior Lord of Fingal. The title and lands of Castleknock were held by the Tyrell family until 1370 when Hugh Tyrell and his wife died of the Plague. It passed by inheritance to the Burnell family. The first Baron, [[Hugh Tyrrel]], gave lands in the barony at Kilmainham to the [[Venerable Order of St John|Knights of St. John]] who continue in the area today in the form of [[St. John Ambulance Brigade of Ireland|St. John Ambulance]]. Later, [[Civil parishes in Ireland|civil parishes]], based on the boundaries of the [[Ecclesiastical parish]]es of the [[Established church]] were used to sub-divide the barony.\n\nIn 1185, Richard de Tyrell, son of the first Baron of Castleknock, gave a grant to the Benedictine Monks of the Abbey of Little Malvern, Worcestershire, to endow a religious house at Castleknock in honour of Saint Brigid<ref>Harris's Table in Ware-Harris, Antiquitie, 1745 and Mervyn Archdall, Monasticon Hibernicum, 1786</ref>. Later they built a chapel, the White Chapel at Coolmine, which served the parish of Clonsilla. In 1219 The great tithes of the parish were appropriated by Archbishop Henry de Londres to the Priory of Malvern on condition that they should add five monks to their number. In 1225 the monks granted half of the tithes of the manor of Castleknock to the use of St Patrick\u2019s Cathedral, renouncing to the Archbishop all rights to the vicarage and its small tithes and oblations. In 1226 the first Prebendary of Castleknock, Richard De Gnouessale, was appointed. However, by 1468 the Church and lands at Castleknock were transferred to the ownership of the Abbey of St. Mary near Dublin. Following the [[English Reformation]] and the [[dissolution of the monasteries]] under [[Henry VIII of England]], the Priory at Castleknock was destroyed and in 1609 a church was built on the site for the use of the [[Church of Ireland]]. The foundation stone of the church, which is in use today, still on the site of the Abbey, was laid in 1803.<ref>Church of Ireland - history http://www.castleknock.dublin.anglican.org/history/history.html</ref> The spire was added in 1864 by friends of the late [[James Hans Hamilton]] as a memorial to the 1st Baron HolmPatrick of Abbottown and [[Member of Parliament|MP]]for the County of Dublin. \n\nIn the townland of Diswellstown there is a historic \"rag well\" - a holy well near which rags were left. Although it still flows, it was \"buried\" by the County Council, and its site is now marked by a carved flagstone. Nearby the Diswellstown Stream, which rises near Castleknock village, flows west and then turns sharply south, taking in a streamlet from Carpenterstown, before running down to the Liffey in a narrow steep valley.\n\nCastleknock eventually came to be divided among a number of important families and their country estates. These included the Guinness at [[Farmleigh]], and Knockmaroon, the Laidlaws at Abbey Lodge, the Godleys at Oatlands, and the Brookes at Sommerton House.<ref>https://reynoldshistorycastleknockblog.wordpress.com/2018/04/27/knockmaroon-estate-local-history-castleknock/</ref>\n\nThe Earl of Iveagh's principle seat was at [[Farmleigh House]] until 1999 when it was purchased by the Government of Ireland. It was restored and converted into a State Guest House and opened to the public in 2001. Although they left Farmleigh in 1999, the Guinness family are still present in Castleknock at Knockmaroon House which is located on Carpenterstown Road and the seat of [[Lord Moyne]], The [[Brooke Baronets]] lived st Sommerton House until they sold it in 1911 to the Laidlaw family who were resident at Sommerton and Abbey Lodge until the 1980s<ref>https://reynoldshistorycastleknockblog.wordpress.com/tag/laidlaw-family/</ref>.\n\n===Civil parish===\nWithin the civil parish of Castleknock, there are 22 [[townlands]] per the table below. Like all civil parishes in Ireland, this civil parish is derived from, and co-extensive with, a pre-existing parish of the [[Church of Ireland]]. In 1773, an act of council united the parish with the curacies of Clonsilla and Mulhuddart. In 1837, Lewis' directory reported that the living (of the ecclesiastical parish) was a vicarage in the diocese of [[Archdiocese of Dublin|Dublin]] which was: \"... endowed with a portion of the great tithes, and united to the prebend of Castleknock and the rectory of Clonsillagh and curacy of Mullahidart, with cure of souls: it is in the patronage of the Bishop.\".<ref>[http://www.genuki.org.uk/big/irl/DUB/Castleknock Lewis,] \"Topographical Dictionary of Ireland\", 1837</ref> The two churches noted by Lewis in the vicarial union, one at Castleknock, the other at Clonsilla, are extant and in use by the Church of Ireland community. The former was rebuilt by a loan of \u00a31000 from the [[Board of First Fruits]] and large subscriptions, in 1810. In 1831, the population of the parish, including Blanchardstown was 4251 people of which 3409 were Catholic.<ref>''The History of the County of Dublin'', John D'Alton, 1838</ref>\n \nThe core of the parish is centred on the townland and village of the same name. The townland at the northern extremity is Huntstown, not to be confused with [[Huntstown and Littlepace]] in the neighbouring parish of [[Clonsilla]].To the south, it is bounded by the [[River Liffey]] and the [[Phoenix Park]]. To the west, it is bounded by [[Coolmine railway station]] and [[Blanchardstown Shopping Centre]]. To the east lies the 8th lock of the [[Royal Canal]] and the Cabra Gate of the Phoenix Park.\n \nFor convenience, the table below groups the parish's townlands by their location in one of the modern [[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|local authority]] areas. Some townlands, however, straddle both areas.\n \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! style=\"width:80px\" | Modern Local<br>[[Local government in the Republic of Ireland|Authority Area]]\n! style=\"width:200px\" | Name in Irish\n! style=\"width:200px\" | Name in English\n! style=\"width:40px\" | Acres\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[Dublin|Dublin City]]\n|Baile an \u00c1saigh\n|[[Ashtown, Dublin|Ashtown]] <small>(partly)</small>\n|278\n|-\n|Baile Pheil\u00e9id\n|Pelletstown\n|259\n|- \n|An Chabrach\n|[[Cabra, Dublin|Cabra]]\n|457\n|-\n|Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha (cuid de Ph\u00e1irc an Fhionnuisce)\n|Castleknock (part of Phoenix Park)<br><small>(partly)</small>\n|1020<br>(787)\n|-\n| rowspan=\"20\" |[[Fingal]]\n|Baile an Aba\n|[[Abbotstown]]<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Abbotstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17224.aspx |title=Abbotstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|101\n|- \n|Baile an \u00c1saigh\n|[[Ashtown, Dublin|Ashtown]] <small>(partly)</small><ref group=\"4\" name=\"Ashtown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17263.aspx |title=Ashtown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|278\n|- \n|Baile an Chairpint\u00e9araigh\n|Carpenterstown</small><ref group=\"4\" name=\"Carpenterstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17266.aspx |title=Carpenterstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|166\n|- \n|Baile an D\u00e9anaigh\n|Deanestown</small><ref group=\"4\" name=\"Deanestown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17228.aspx |title=Deanestown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|173\n|- \n|Baile an Diosualaigh\n|Diswellstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Diswellstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17269.aspx |title=Diswellstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|418\n|- \n|Baile an Huntaigh\n|Huntstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Huntstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17230.aspx |title=Huntstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|299\n|- \n|Baile an Ph\u00f3irt\u00e9araigh\n|Porterstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Porterstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17271.aspx |title=Porterstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|219\n|- \n|Baile Bhlains\u00e9ir\n|Blanchardstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Blanchardstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/1412097.aspx |title=Blanchardstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|454\n|- \n|Baile Mhist\u00e9il\n|Mitchelstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Mitchelstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17232.aspx |title=Mitchelstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|154\n|-  \n|Baile Scriobail\n|Scribblestown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Scribblestown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17270.aspx |title=Scribblestown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n|272\n|- \n|Baile She\u00e1in\n|Johnstown<ref group=\"4\" name=\"Johnstown\">{{cite web|url=http://www.logainm.ie/17558.aspx |title=Johnstown &#124; logainm.ie|publisher=logainm.ie|accessdate=26 March 2016}}</ref>\n| 67\n|- \n|An Chabrach\n|[[Cabra, Dublin|Cabra]]\n|457\n|- \n|Caisle\u00e1n Cnucha (cuid de Ph\u00e1irc an Fhionnuisce)\n|Castleknock <br>(part of Phoenix Park)<br><small>(partly)</small>\n|1020<br>(787)\n|- \n|Ceapach\n|Cappoge or Cappagh\n|698\n|- \n|Cnoc na gCaorach\n|Sheephill\n|349\n|- \n|An Chorr Dhubh\n|[[Corduff]]\n|353\n|- \n|D\u00fan Sinche\n|[[Dunsink]]\n|423\n|- \n|P\u00e1irc Anna\n|Annfield\n| 19\n|-\n|Snugborough\n|Snugborough\n| 53\n|- \n|Steach Gob\n|Astagob\n| 93\n|-\n|}\n\n==Castleknock today==\n[[File:Arts and Crafts style cottages, Main Street, Castlekock, Dublin 15.jpg|thumb|Arts and Crafts style cottages, Main Street, Castlekmock]]\n[[File:St Bridgets Castleknock 2012.jpg|thumb|\"St. Briget's, Church of Ireland\"]]\n[[File:St Thomas the Apostle.jpg|thumb|\"St Thomas the Apostle\",<br> Laurel Lodge, Castleknock]]\n[[File:Castleknock Catholic Church.jpg|thumb|\"Our Lady Mother of the Church\",<br> Catholic church, Castleknock.]]\n[[File:Stained glass window, St. Thomas Church, Castleknock, Dublin. Ireland.jpg|thumb|Stained glass window, St. Thomas the Apostle, Laurel Lodge]]\n\nThe village is a busy commercial centre with several supermarkets and other retail outlets. There is a post-office and several cafes and restaurants. There are three primary schools in the village, Castleknock National School (Church of Ireland), St. Brigid's Primary School (Roman Catholic), and Castleknock Educate Together (Non-Denominational). Outside the village there is also Scoil Thom\u00e1is Co-educational Primary School in Laurel Lodge district and St. Patrick's Co-educational Primary School in Diswellstown. Castleknock Co-educational Community School (Multi-Denominational) is located on Carpenterstown Road.  Mount Sackville Roman Catholic independent secondary school for girls was founded in 1864 by the Sisters of St. Joseph of Cluny. \n\n===Facilities===\n\n* In the neighbouring townland of Diswellstown there is a historic \"rag well\" - a holy well near which rags were left. Although it still flows, it was \"buried\" by the County Council, and its site is now marked by a carved flagstone. Nearby the Diswellstown Stream, which rises near Castleknock village, flows west and then turns sharply south, taking in a streamlet from Carpenterstown, before running down to the Liffey in a narrow steep valley.\n*[[Farmleigh]]- an estate of {{convert|78|acres|0|abbr=on|lk=out}} situated to the north-west of Dublin's Phoenix Park. The Government bought the estate from the Guinness family for \u20ac29.2 million in 1999 and spent \u20ac23 million refurbishing it.<ref>Irish Times - Farmleigh in 2010 http://m.irishtimes.com/newspaper/frontpage/2010/0125/1224263037689.html?via=frontpage</ref>\n* Castleknock Lawn Tennis Club was founded in 1927 by Mrs. Ellen Molloy and bothers James and Owen Sweeney brothers. It was registered with the Irish League of Tennis Associations (now Tennis Ireland) in 1934 and has grown into one of the largest tennis clubs in Ireland. \n* Gaelic games are played at [[Castleknock GAA|Castleknock Hurling and Football Club]] whose new {{convert|23|acre|m2|adj=on}} \"Castleknock Community Park\" will be the club's home.<ref>http://www.dublin15.ie/pages/CV114/CV114n01.htm Community Voice - GAA at Somerton</ref> Founded in 1998, Castleknock [[Gaelic Athletic Association|GAA]] Club has over 1500 members from over 650 families. [[St. Brigids|St. Brigid's GAA Club]] play in Dr. Tom Russell Park (Old Navan Road, Castleknock) and is one of the largest clubs in the country. The club has five adult teams, including two senior teams and an intermediate team. Russell Park also boasts the largest all-weather pitch in Ireland.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stbrigidsgaa.com/ClubDevelopment |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-03-01 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210133544/http://www.stbrigidsgaa.com/ClubDevelopment/ |archivedate=2010-02-10 }}</ref>[[File:Castleknock Golf Club, Dublin 15 - geograph.org.uk - 1741952.jpg|thumb|Castleknock Golf Club]]. \n* Castleknock Golf Club, located 1 mile west of the village beside [[Castleknock Hotel]]. Luttrellstown Golf Club is located 2 miles west of the village. \n* Soccer is also popular in the area with [[St. Mochta\u2019s F.C.]] with over 400 playing members and Castleknock Celtic FC has over 600 playing members.\n\n====Community groups====\n* Local First Aid training, event cover and community care in the Castleknock area is provided by [http://www.stjohncastleknock.ie St. John Ambulance Castleknock Combined Division] and the [http://www.orderofmaltaireland.org/index.php/contact/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=197 Order of Malta Castleknock] <ref>[http://www.orderofmaltaireland.org/index.php/contact/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=197] Order of Malta Castleknock</ref>\n* There are a number of residents associations such as \"Riverwood Residents Association\" and \"Carpenterstown Park Residents Association\".<ref>[http://www.communityvoice.ie/pages/CV162/CV162c03.htm Community Voice, ''Carpenterstown residents\u2019 association launch new website.''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120330075610/http://www.communityvoice.ie/pages/CV162/CV162c03.htm |date=2012-03-30 }}</ref>\n* There is an active Tidy Towns Committee.\n* Castleknock Community Centre,<ref>[http://www.castleknockcommunitycentre.ie] Castleknock Community Centre website.</ref> in the Laurel Lodge area, hosts a range of social, sporting and charitable groups.\n* [http://www.castleknockscouts.ie Castleknock Scout Group], the 175th Castleknock, Dublin Troop, operate in the main village area and the Laurel Lodge and Carpenterstown areas.\n\n=== Religious institutions ===\n[[St. Brigid]] is the patron saint of the village.\n\nIn the [[Church of Ireland]], the church of St. Brigid, cited on the ruins of an ancient monastery, is located in the middle of the village. In the [[Catholic Church]], there are two [[Ecclesiastic parish|parishes]] in the suburb: \"Our Lady Mother of the Church\" which is centred close to the village and [[St Thomas the Apostle parish, Laurel Lodge]].\n  \nBoth St. Brigid's and St. Thomas the Apostle contain windows from the [[Harry Clarke]] Studios. The window in St. Brigid's was commissioned in 1927 by R.F. Brookes of Somerton House, Castleknock, to commemorate members of his family, whereas the Harry Clarke window in St. Thomas the Apostle was donated by the Domincan Order after their convent at D\u00fan Laoghaire closed in 1991. It depicts the Immaculate Conception of Mary.\n\n===Government and representation===\nCastleknock is located in the \"Castleknock ward\" for the purposes of elections to [[Fingal County Council]] and is in the [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)]] and in [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)]].\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of towns and villages in the Republic of Ireland|List of towns and villages in Ireland]]\n\n==References==\nFrom {{cite web |url=http://www.logainm.ie/?uiLang=en |title=Irish placenames database |publisher=Department of Community, Rural and Gaeltacht Affairs |work=[[logainm.ie]] |language=English, Irish |accessdate=13 April 2020}}\n:{{reflist |30em|group=4}}\n\nOther:\n<ref name=\"http://www.castleknock.net/\">{{cite web|title=Castleknock Gaa Club|url=http://www.castleknock.net/|website=Castleknock.net|publisher=Web Design Dublin by Webtrade|accessdate=28 November 2016}}</ref>\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irishstatutebook.ie/2001/en/act/pub/0037/sec0010.html Local Government Act, 2001]\n* [http://www.castleknock.dublin.anglican.org/history/castleknock.html History of Castleknock Church of Ireland]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20100218031824/http://www.transport21.ie/Projects/Metro_-_Luas/Metro_-_Luas.html Official \"Transport 21\" site ]\n* [http://www.castleknock.net/ Castleknock Hurling & Football Club ]\n* [http://www.castleknockcollege.ie/ Official Castleknock College website ]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090626121538/http://www.mountsackville.ie/index.asp Official Mount Sackville School website ]\n* [http://www.castleknockhotel.com/?gclid=CPeDg4CVq9ACFdXNGwod958A2w Castleknock Hotel & Country Club]\n* [http://www.stpatricksns.ie/ St Patrick's National School, Diswellstown],\n\n{{Dublin residential areas}}\n{{Fingal}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Castleknock|  ]]\n[[Category:Civil parishes of the barony of Castleknock]]\n[[Category:Townlands of Fingal]]\n", "name_user": "Ollamhnua", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFacilities:Removed the following text as information is already provided elsewhere in the article \" *Farmleigh- an estate of {{convert|78|acres|0|abbr=on|lk=out}} situated to the north-west of Dublin's Phoenix Park. The Government bought the estate from the Guinness family for \u20ac29.2 million in 1999 and spent \u20ac23 million refurbishing it.<ref>Irish Times - Farmleigh in 2010 http://m.irishtimes.com/newspaper/frontpage/2010/0125/1224263037689.html?via=frontpage</ref> * Castleknock Lawn Ten", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Castleknock"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Metro Manila of the Philippines}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Metro Manila\n| map1            = COVID-19 Outbreak Cases in Metro Manila.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Confirmed cases in Metro Manila by local government unit (as of April 12){{refn|group=note|name=PHmapnote|Breakdown of confirmed cases is according to the [https://ncovtracker.doh.gov.ph/ COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health. Take note that the map may not reflect all affected localities and is primarily based on the recorded place of residence of confirmed cases. Patients with confirmed COVID-19 infection may be referred to a health facility than their recorded place of residence.}}}}\n{{legend|#280b0b|500+ confirmed}}{{legend|#510000|100\u2013499 confirmed}}{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Metro Manila]]\n| first_case      = [[Manila]]\n| arrival_date    = January 30, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China\n| recovery_cases  = 132\n| deaths          = 179\n| confirmed_cases = 3,510\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = {{ubl|{{URL|http://www.covid19.gov.ph}}|{{URL|https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker}}}}\n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Metro Manila]], Philippines on January 30, 2020, when the first case of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) was confirmed in the [[Manila|City of Manila]]. By March 13, Metro Manila was reported to be the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|worst affected region in the Philippines]] with 70 percent of all cases in the country at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/videos/2020/3/13/Most-cases-recorded-in-Metro-Manila.html |title=Most cases recorded in Metro Manila |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Bonquin, C. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref> A [[state of calamity]] and [[2020 Philippine community quarantines|community quarantine]] have been in place in the region since March 15.<ref name=\"philstar01\"/>\n\nAs of April 13, 2020, there have been 4,932 confirmed cases of COVID-19 in the Philippines, 3,510 of which are residents of Metro Manila. There are 132 recoveries and 179 deaths in the region, with [[Quezon City]], Manila, [[Pasig]] and [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] reporting the most fatalities.<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\">{{cite web |title=COVID-19 Tracker |url=https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker |website=doh.gov.ph |publisher=[[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] |accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Background==\n{{Main|2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\nThe first confirmed case of COVID-19 in the Philippines was recorded in Metro Manila on January 30, 2020. It involved a 38-year-old Chinese woman from [[Wuhan]], the origin of the disease, who arrived in [[Manila]] after travelling to [[Cebu City]] and [[Dumaguete]] in central Philippines from [[Hong Kong]].<ref name=\"abs1\">{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/01/30/20/philippines-confirms-first-case-of-new-coronavirus |title=Philippines confirms first case of new coronavirus |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Sabillo, K. |date=January 30, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Three days later, the [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Philippine Department of Health]] (DOH) confirmed that a second Chinese national tested positive for COVID-19, identified as the 44-year-old male companion of the first confirmed patient.<ref name=\"gma1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/724482/philippines-confirms-2nd-novel-coronavirus-case-patient-dies/story/ |title=Philippines confirms 2nd novel coronavirus case, 1st death outside China |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Colcol, E. |date=February 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\nBoth patients received treatment at Manila's [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] with the latter being reported to have died from the disease on February 2, becoming the first known fatality outside [[China]].<ref name=\"gma1\"/> On March 6, the DOH reported the first case of local community transmission of the deadly virus, a 62-year-old Filipino man from suburban [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], just east of Metro Manila, with no prior travel history to affected countries.<ref name=\"cnn1\">{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/6/Philippines-coronavirus-local-case.html |title=Philippines records its first local case of coronavirus |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Tan, L. |date=March 6, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> He and his 59-year-old Filipino wife were initially admitted to the Cardinal Santos Medical Center in [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]] where they were diagnosed with the virus before being transferred to the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in [[Muntinlupa]] where they both died on March 11.<ref name=\"philstar2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths |title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, 2020, following the declaration of a public health emergency, Philippine President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] placed the entire capital region under community [[quarantine]] for 30 days starting March 15, 2020.<ref name=\"philstar1\">{{cite web |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000209/travel-and-manila-suspended-march-15-code-red-sublevel-2-raised-over-covid-19 |title=Travel to and from Manila suspended from March 15 as Code Red Sublevel 2 raised over COVID-19 |last=Luna |first=Franco |website=The Philippine Star |access-date=March 12, 2020}}</ref> Most areas in Metro Manila have also issued curfews to help limit the spread of the virus.<ref name=\"gma2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729731/manila-to-have-curfew-from-8-p-m-5-a-m-amid-covid-19-threat-says-mayor-isko/story/ |title=Several Metro Manila LGUs impose 8 p.m.-5 a.m. COVID-19 curfew |publisher=[[GMA News]] |author=Rita, J. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> On March 16, an [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine]] order was issued by the president covering Metro Manila and the entire island of [[Luzon]].<ref name=\"gazette1\"/>\n\nOn April 7, DOH secretary [[Francisco Duque]] reported that Metro Manila's COVID-19 cases continued to rise as 80 percent of the country's 3,764 confirmed cases were from the region. Duque also identified the cities with the most number of cases by the third week of the mass quarantine: Quezon City with 583, Manila with 221, [[Makati]] with 160, [[Para\u00f1aque]] with 155, and San Juan with 134 confirmed cases. The cities with the most reported deaths so far were identified as Quezon City with 34, Manila with 30, San Juan with 24, Pasig with 15, and [[Caloocan]] and Para\u00f1aque with 14 fatalities each.<ref name=\"gma0407\">{{cite web|url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/nation/733067/philippines-covid-19-cases-concentrated-in-metro-manila-says-duque/story/ |title=Philippines\u2019 COVID-19 cases concentrated in Metro Manila, says Duque |publisher=[[GMA Network]] |author=Ornedo, J.M. |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref> On the same day, President Duterte announced that the Luzon-wide quarantine measures have been extended to April 30.<ref name=\"ecqex\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Luzon-lockdown-enhanced-community-quarantine-extension.html |title=Luzon-wide lockdown extended until April 30 to stop COVID-19 spread |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{Main|Timeline of the 2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable floatright <!---mw-collapsible--->\" style=\"text-align:left; font-size:90%; width:auto; clear:right; margin:0 0 0.5em 1em;\"\n|+COVID-19 cases in NCR, Philippines<ref name=\"COVID-19 tracker\"/><br/><small>by city/municipality of residence<br/>Updated April 13, 2020 11:30 pm UTC+8</small>\n! {{abbr|LGU|Local government unit}}\n! {{Hover title|Confirmed cases|Cases}}\n! Deaths\n! {{abbr|Recov.|Recoveries}}\n|-\n| [[Caloocan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 110\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 11\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n|-\n| [[Las Pi\u00f1as]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 106\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 4\n|-\n| [[Makati]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 296\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 21\n|-\n| [[Malabon]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 22\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 5\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 1\n|-\n| [[Mandaluyong]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 253\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 7\n|-\n| [[Manila]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 443\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 24\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 10\n|-\n| [[Marikina]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 99\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 5\n|-\n| [[Muntinlupa]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 108\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Navotas]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 17\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Para\u00f1aque]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 276\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 12\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 8\n|-\n| [[Pasay]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 114\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 3\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 6\n|-\n| [[Pasig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 215\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 20\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 16\n|-\n| [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 7\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|-\n| [[Quezon City]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 940\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 53\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 28\n|-\n| [[San Juan, Metro Manila|San Juan]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 174\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 11\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 13\n|-\n| [[Taguig]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 182\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 5\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 12\n|-\n| [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 51\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | 2\n| style=\"text-align:right;\"  | {{color|darkgray|0}}\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:left;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 2,398\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 300\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 274\n|-\n|}\n* January 30 \u2013 The Philippines confirms its first case of coronavirus in Metro Manila and the entire country after a 38-year-old woman from [[Wuhan]] tested positive for COVID-19. She was hospitalized at [[San Lazaro Hospital, Manila|San Lazaro Hospital]] in Manila.<ref name=\"abs1\"/>\n* February 2 \u2013 The first coronavirus-related death outside China was recorded in Manila. A 44-year-old Chinese man died while being treated at the San Lazaro Hospital.<ref name=\"gma1\"/>\n* March 6 \u2013 The first case of community transmission is reported by the DOH, a 62-year-old Filipino man from nearby [[Cainta]], [[Rizal]], with no known history of travel abroad and who regularly visited a Muslim prayer hall in [[Greenhills (mixed-use development)|Greenhills]], San Juan.\n* March 7 \u2013 [[Taguig]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Modesto |first1=Catherine |title=Taguig-based firm says an employee tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/Deloitte-employee-coronavirus-positive.html?fbclid=IwAR2eajMCxa0Y6zVSNthbsokVZxfrigXjxrUufx5GA2PRVyMqC429Y77erv0 |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 9 \n** [[Marikina]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Marikina coronavirus cases jump to 5 |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1239830/marikina-govt-on-coronavirus-cases |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Pasig]],<ref>{{cite news |title=4 new confirmed coronavirus cases recorded in Metro Manila |url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/9/Coronavirus-cases-Quezon-City-Philippines.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> and [[Quezon City]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Rita |first1=Joviland |title=QC Mayor Joy Belmonte announces confirmed COVID-19 case in the city |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/728862/qc-mayor-joy-belmonte-announces-confirmed-covid-19-case-in-the-city/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> each record its first COVID-19 case.\n** The local governments of San Juan, Marikina, and [[Pasay]] order the suspension of classes for all levels amid the announcement of the first case of community transmission in the metropolis.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/09/1999216/san-juan-marikina-pasay-suspend-classes-over-covid-19 |title=San Juan, Marikina, Pasay suspend classes over COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Servallos, N.J. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 10\n** President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] order the closure of all schools, colleges, and universities in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/253912-walang-pasok-duterte-declares-class-suspensions-metro-manila-coronavirus-threat-march-10-14-2020 |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila March 10\u201314 over coronavirus threat |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=March 9, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority#Metro Manila Council|Metro Manila Council]], consisting of the Metro Manila mayors and headed by chairman [[Danilo Lim]], convene to discuss measures to prevent the spread of the virus as confirmed cases in the region climbed to 33.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/multimedia/photo/03/10/20/metro-mayors-meet-on-local-lockdowns-after-coronavirus-cases-rise |title=Metro mayors meet on local lockdowns after coronavirus cases rise |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Cellona, J. |date=March 10, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 11 \n** [[Caloocan]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=One more COVID-19 patient in Tala hospital \u2013 Malapitan |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/11/one-more-covid-19-patient-in-tala-hospital-malapitan/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 11, 2020}}</ref>\n** Manila Mayor [[Isko Moreno]] goes into self-quarantine and isolates himself in the [[Manila City Hall]] after arriving from an official trip to [[London]], U.K.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254164-isko-moreno-self-quarantines-manila-city-hall |title=Isko Moreno self-quarantines at Manila city hall |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Talabong, R. |date=March 11, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 12\n** Las Pi\u00f1as records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as records 1st COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/12/20/las-pias-records-1st-covid-19-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n** President Duterte announces a partial lockdown on Metro Manila, placing the entire Metro Manila under community quarantine for thirty days beginning on March 15. The suspension of classes in all levels in Metro Manila is extended to April 12.<ref name=\"philstar01\">{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000353/walang-pasok-duterte-suspends-metro-manila-classes-until-april-12 |title=Walang Pasok: Duterte suspends Metro Manila classes until April 12 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Patag, K.J. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Incidents of [[panic buying]] are reported across the region, triggered by the president's partial lockdown order.<ref name=\"panic buying\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240902/look-panic-buying-amid-lockdown-fears-in-metro |title=LOOK: Panic-buying amid lockdown fears in Metro Manila |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 12, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 13\n** The local chief executives of Caloocan, [[Malabon]], [[Navotas]], and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]]: [[Oscar Malapitan]], [[Antolin Oreta]], [[Toby Tiangco]], and [[Rex Gatchalian]], respectively, go into self-quarantine after learning they had come into contact with a confirmed coronavirus patient at a March 5 event in Caloocan's [[North Luzon Expressway]]\u2013Harbor Link.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1240982/camanava-mayors-under-quarantine |title=Camanava mayors under quarantine |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Adonis, M. |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** The DOH reports that four COVID-19 patients in the region had died.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/qc-state-of-calamity.html |title=Quezon City declares state of calamity amid COVID-19 threat |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=CNN PH staff |date=March 13, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 14 \u2013 [[Mandaluyong]] records its first three COVID-19 cases.<ref name=\"Mandaluyong 1st case\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong declares state of calamity over spread of COVID-19 |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/16/20/mandaluyong-declares-state-of-calamity-over-spread-of-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 15\n** [[Muntinlupa]] records its first COVID-19 case.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa 1st case\">{{cite web |title=Muntinlupa City Declares State Of Calamity Due To COVID-19 Emergency |url=https://www.muntinlupacity.gov.ph/?p=18062 |publisher=City Government of Muntinlupa |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** A total of 56 checkpoints are set up in numerous points of entry to Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\">{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1242619/police-seal-metro-manila-to-fight-virus |title=Police seal Metro Manila to fight virus |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Yamsuan, C.C., Agoncillo, J.A. |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n** Following a directive from the Metro Manila Council and the confirmation of COVID-19 cases, the city mayors of Makati, Manila, Pasig, and San Juan declare a [[State of emergency|state of calamity]].<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/>\n* March 16 \u2013 President Duterte [[2020 Luzon enhanced community quarantine|imposes an enhanced community quarantine]] covering the entire [[Luzon]], including Metro Manila, suspending [[Transportation in the Philippines|mass public transportation]]; restricting land, air, and sea travel; imposing strict home quarantine; and closing most private establishments until April 13.<ref name=\"gazette1\">{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.officialgazette.gov.ph/2020/03/16/memorandum-from-the-executive-secretary-on-community-quarantine-over-the-entire-luzon-and-further-guidelines-for-the-management-of-the-coronavirus-disease-2019-covid-19-situation/|title=Memorandum from the Executive Secretary On Community Quarantine Over the Entire Luzon and Further Guidelines for the Management of the Coronavirus Disease 2019 (COVID-19) Situation|date=March 16, 2020|work=Official Gazette GOV.PH|access-date=March 17, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* March 17 \u2013 The Manila bourse becomes the first major market in the world to shut down over coronavirus fears. It suspends trading for two days following a [[2020 stock market crash|global stock market crash]] which saw the main [[Philippine Stock Exchange]] index plunge more than 30 percent.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-16/philippines-shuts-financial-markets-after-virus-spurs-stock-rout |title=Philippines Becomes First Country to Shut Financial Markets Thanks to Virus |publisher=[[Bloomberg News|Bloomberg]] |author1=Tu, Lianting |author2=Sayson, Ian C. |date=March 17, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 19 \u2013 Valenzuela records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casilao |first1=Joahna Lei |title=Valenzuela reports first COVID-19 case |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/730416/valenzuela-reports-first-covid-19-case/story/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 23 \u2013 Malabon records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Bernardo |first1=Jaehwa |title=Malabon records first COVID-19 case |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/malabon-records-first-covid-19-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 24 \u2013 Several private hospitals in Metro Manila report operating at full-capacity due to the pandemic and urged patients to look for alternative hospitals.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247913/5-metro-hospitals-reach-full-capacity-for-covid-19-cases |title=5 Metro Manila hospitals reach full capacity for COVID-19 cases |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yamsuan, C.C. |author2=Yee, J. |date=March 25, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 28\n** Navotas records its first COVID-19 case.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Valenzuela |first1=Nikka |title=Navotas records first coronavirus case |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1250197/navotas-records-first-coronavirus-case |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 29, 2020}}</ref>\n** The [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport]], except [[Ninoy Aquino International Airport Terminal 1|Terminal 1]], closes following the suspension of domestic and international flights resulting from travel restriction impositions.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/business/2020/03/28/2003833/airlines-mount-cargo-only-flights-transport-vital-goods |title=Airlines mount \u2018cargo-only\u2019 flights to transport vital goods |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=Mercurio, R. |date=March 28, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n** [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] General Manager Jojo Garcia is confirmed as coronavirus positive.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/28/2003984/mmda-general-manager-positive-covid-19 |title=MMDA general manager positive for COVID-19 |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author=San Juan, R. |date=March 28, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n* March 31 \u2013 The [[Philippine National Police]] reports that 10,850 curfew violators have been apprehended across the region since the start of the enhanced community quarantines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1251886/pnp-records-more-than-70k-violators-of-quarantine-protocols |title=Over 70,000 violated Luzon-wide quarantine protocols \u2013 PNP |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Marquez, C. |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 1\n** The local government of Manila reports its largest single-day increase in coronavirus infections so far with 41 new cases, bringing the city's total to 116.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/1/manila-records-largest-single-day-jump-coronavirus-.html |title=City of Manila records largest single-day jump in COVID-19\u00a0cases, total now at 116 |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n** More than 800 Filipino repatriates from four virus-stricken cruise ships in the U.S. arrive at the Ninoy Aquino International Airport.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256625-filipinos-united-states-cruise-ships-arrive-philippines-april-1-2020 |title=881 Filipinos from cruise ships in U.S. now back in PH |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 2\n**The Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases (IATF-EID) announced that Metro Manila remains the worst hit by the coronavirus crisis in the country after 1,511 cases were confirmed in the region, or more than 50 percent of the total confirmed cases in the Philippines.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/02/20/metro-manila-remains-ph-epicenter-of-coronavirus-crisis-galvez |title=Metro Manila remains PH epicenter of coronavirus crisis - Galvez |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |author=Maru, D. |date=April 2, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n**COVID-19 inter-agency taskforce spokesman [[Karlo Nograles]] announces the mandatory wearing of [[surgical mask|face mask]]s in public for residents in all regions under enhanced community quarantine in Luzon.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/256753-filipinos-luzon-required-wear-face-masks |title=Luzon residents now required to wear face masks when leaving homes |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Tomacruz, S. |date=April 2, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n* April 3 \u2013 The [[National Capital Region Police Office]] confirm its first COVID-19 casualty among its ranks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/03/news/latest-stories/2-policemen-succumb-to-virus/709280/ |title=2 policemen succumb to virus |publisher=[[The Manila Times]] |date=April 3, 2020 |accessdate=April 5, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 6\n**A ten-man medical team from China arrive in Manila to share their experience in prevention and control of the coronavirus disease.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/04/06/2005737/chinese-coronavirus-doctors-arrive-manila |title=Chinese coronavirus doctors arrive in Manila |publisher=[[The Philippine Star]] |author1=Santos, R. |author2=Brago, P.L. |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**[[Human decontamination|Decontamination]] tents are installed in public hospitals and government offices across the region by the Metropolitan Manila Development Authority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/06/20/mmda-sets-up-decontamination-tents-in-public-hospitals-govt-offices |title=MMDA sets up decontamination tents in public hospitals, gov't offices |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 6, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 7\n**President Duterte approves an extension of the enhanced community quarantine in the region until April 30.<ref name=\"ecqex\"/>\n**The Health department launches a [[24/7 service|24/7]] coronavirus hotline for Metro Manila residents.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Telemedicine-consultation-COVID.html |title=DOH launches telemedicine consultation for Metro Manila residents |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |date=April 7, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[Embassy of the United States, Manila]] announce the cancellation of all scheduled visa appointments until May 4.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/08/20/us-embassy-in-manila-all-visa-interviews-until-may-4-cancelled |title=US embassy in Manila: All visa interviews until May 4 cancelled |publisher=[[ABS-CBN News]] |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n*April 8\n**The [[Rizal Memorial Stadium]] in [[Malate, Manila|Malate]] opens as a 116-bed COVID-19 emergency healthcare facility, with 108 more beds expected to be completed by April 17.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://business.inquirer.net/294438/rizal-memorial-stadium-ready-to-accept-initial-116-covid-19-patients |title=Rizal Memorial Stadium ready to accept initial 116 COVID-19 patients |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author=Abadilla, D.D. |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n**The [[World Health Organization]] Western Pacific Regional Office in Manila express its approval of the quarantine measures as it claims it was able to prevent a large-scale community outbreak of the virus in the region.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/8/WHO-PH-lockdown-prevent-large-scale-community-quarantine.html |title=Lockdown saves PH from large-scale community outbreak, WHO says |publisher=[[CNN Philippines]] |author=Ferreras, V. |date=April 8, 2020 |accessdate=April 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\n<center>\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n|linewidth=1\n|showSymbols=1\n|width=700\n|colors= #FF6347, #FFC000, #87CEEB, #000000\n|showValues=\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|x= Mar 6, Mar 8, Mar 9, Mar 10, Mar 11, Mar 12, Mar 13, Mar 14, Mar 15, Mar 16, Mar 17, Mar 18, Mar 19, Mar 20, Mar 21, Mar 22, Mar 23, Mar 24, Mar 25, Mar 26, Mar 27, Mar 28, Mar 29, Mar 30, Mar 31, Apr 1, Apr 2, Apr 3, Apr 4, Apr 5, Apr 6, Apr 7, Apr 8, Apr 9, Apr 10, Apr 11, Apr 12, Apr 13\n|yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n|legend=Legend