Legend\n|y= 0, 0, 0, 3, 10, 10, 15, 36, 50, 51, 75, 82, 91, 100, 140, 180, 233, 293, 344, 381, 446, 618, 857, 914, 1287, 1438, 1665, 1935, 1980, 2093, 2394, 2452, 2524, 2679, 2749, 2913, 3024, 3199\n|y1Title=Active cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n</center>\n== Response ==\n=== National government ===\n[[File:PNP PRO 3 Checkpoints COVID 19 2.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the northern border of Metro Manila with [[Meycauayan]], [[Bulacan]] in [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]].]]\n[[File:COVID-19 border checkpoint in Muntinlupa.jpg|thumb|Police checkpoint near the southern border of Metro Manila with [[San Pedro, Laguna]] in [[Muntinlupa]].]]\nBefore the partial lockdown on Metro Manila declared on March 12, President [[Rodrigo Duterte]] had initially suspended classes across all levels in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14 upon reaching a consensus with the [[Metro Manila Council]] (the mayors of Metro Manila) due to the rapidly increasing number of cases especially in the area.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lopez |first1=Virgil |title=Duterte suspends classes in Metro Manila from March 10 to 14, 2020 |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/serbisyopubliko/walangpasok/728993/duterte-suspends-classes-in-metro-manila-from-march-10-to-14-2020/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, President Duterte announced a partial lockdown covering Metro Manila, that begun on March 15 and will last until April 14. Under the partial lockdown:<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Ana |title=Ghost town: Manila under coronavirus lockdown |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/manila-turns-ghost-town-coronavirus-lockdown-200315121507679.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Al Jazeera |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n* The region is closed to land, air, and sea travel. However, mass transportation within Metro Manila such as the [[Manila Light Rail Transit System|Manila LRT]] and [[Manila Metro Rail Transit System|MRT]] continues to operate under proper [[social distancing]] guidelines.\n* Suspension of classes at all levels in Metro Manila is extended until April 14.\n* Spontaneous and planned mass gatherings are banned.\n* Work in the Executive department is suspended under the lockdown period.\n* The [[Department of Labor and Employment (Philippines)|Department of Labor and Employment]] encourages employers in the private sector to arrange \"flexible work arrangements\".\n\nFollowing the declaration of the partial lockdown, the [[Metropolitan Manila Development Authority]] (MMDA) suspended the enforcement of the [[Unified Vehicular Volume Reduction Program]], more commonly known as the number coding scheme.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Jel |title=Number coding suspended indefinitely due to 'community quarantine' \u2014 MMDA |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/13/number-coding-suspended-indefinitely-due-to-community-quarantine-mmda/ |accessdate=March 13, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref> The Metro Manila Council unanimously approved the imposition of the curfew in a joint resolution. All local governments, except for [[Marikina]] and [[Pateros, Metro Manila|Pateros]], had adopted ordinances imposing the curfew in their respective cities, effective by March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=LIST: Metro Manila cities with COVID-19 curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/16/Metro-Manila-COVID-19-curfew-list.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> In that joint resolution, the council also ordered the closure of shopping malls and other establishments during the lockdown.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cordero |first1=Ted |title=Metro Manila Council wants malls temporarily closed amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/729652/metro-manila-council-wants-malls-temporarily-closed-amid-covid-19-threat/story/?just_in |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nA total of 56 checkpoints were set up to man the borders of Metro Manila on the first day of the partial lockdown.<ref name=\"partial lockdown\"/> At 12 midnight, a total of 26,000 police and military personnel were deployed to contain the pandemic of COVID-19 in the region. Motorists were stopped randomly and asked for their identification along the borders in North Luzon Expressway, [[MacArthur Highway]], and the National Road ([[Maharlika Highway]]). Some checkpoints lacked thermal scanners.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/254565-metro-manila-lockdown-implementation-checkpoints-march-15-2020 |title=Day 1 of Metro Manila lockdown: Different checkpoints, different rules |publisher=[[Rappler]] |author=Cupin, B., Rivas, R. & Tomacruz, S. |date=March 15, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the moratorium on mass public transportation during the enhanced community quarantine, Vice President [[Leni Robredo]] launched free shuttle bus services for those individuals exempted from the quarantine, specifically health professionals, front line government officials, and essential service providers. Robredo's shuttle services travel five routes around Metro Manila, connecting the major hospitals.<ref>{{cite news |title=Robredo donates gear to health workers, pledges free shuttle rides |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/robredo-donation-health-workers.html |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> Some city governments also deployed such transportation services.\n\nTo address concerns regarding the hoarding and [[panic buying]] of essential goods, some city governments issued ordinances to limit the amount of such goods an individual or establishment could purchase.<ref name=\"Muntinlupa anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa declares state of calamity due to COVID-19 |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/17/muntinlupa-declares-state-of-calamity-due-to-covid-19/ |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Pasig anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christia Marie |title=Pasig City OKs anti-hoarding, panic buying ordinance |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243408/pasig-city-anti-panic-buying-ordinance-story |accessdate=March 18, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Valenzuela anti-hoarding\">{{cite news |last1=David |first1=Jun |title=Valenzuela passes anti-hoarding, anti-panic buying measure |url=https://manilastandard.net/index.php/lgu/ncr/319768/valenzuela-passes-anti-hoarding-anti-panic-buying-measure.html |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Department of Health (Philippines)|Department of Health]] has on March 20, 2020 has announced that it has designated three health facilities as COVID-19 referral hospitals namely the [[Philippine General Hospital|UP-Philippine General Hospital]] (UP-PGH) in Manila, the Dr. Jose M. Rodriguez Memorial Hospital and Sanitarium in Caloocan and the [[Lung Center of the Philippines]] in Quezon City. The UP-PGH has stopped admitting non-emergency cases and the Lung Center has dedicated one of its wings of 40 beds for COVID-19 patients. The Philippine Blood Center likewise will not admit any suspected COVID-19 cases with the health department encouraging the public to continue donate blood for COVID-19 patients with critical and severe conditions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Galvez |first1=Daphne |title=PGH, 2 other institutions chosen as COVID-19 referral hospitals |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1245731/covid-19-referral-hospitals |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 20, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe national government announced on March 25 a cash aid for poor families affected by the pandemic in the region amounting to {{Philippine peso|8,000}} of monthly subsidy over two months as part of the {{Philippine peso|200 billion}} cash assistance program under the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]] signed by President Duterte.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1252020/cash-aid-for-poor-p-8000-in-metro-p-5000-in-regions |title=Cash aid for poor: P8,000 in Metro; P5,000 in regions |publisher=[[Philippine Daily Inquirer]] |author1=Yap, DJ |author2=Yee, J. |author3=Salaverria, L.B. |date=April 1, 2020 |accessdate=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\nVice President Robredo converted a [[dormitory]] in [[Quezon City#Cubao|Cubao, Quezon City]], to provide free accommodations for front line health professionals during the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Esguerra |first1=Darryl John |title=Robredo launches free dormitory in QC for COVID-19 frontliners |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1248747/robredo-launches-free-dormitory-in-qc-for-covid-19-frontliners |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 26, the [[Department of Agriculture (Philippines)|Department of Agriculture]] launched its first mobile [[farmers' market]] in the region, the ''Kadiwa on Wheels'', in [[Quezon City]], to ensure enough food supply amid the closure of most retail establishments due to the region-wide quarantine.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.untvweb.com/news/farm-products-at-cheaper-price-available-at-kadiwa-on-wheels-da/ |title=Farm products at cheaper price available at \u2018Kadiwa on Wheels\u2019 \u2014 DA |publisher=[[UNTV (Philippines)]] |author=Pelayo, M. |date=March 26, 2020 |accessdate=April 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Ninoy Aquino Stadium as a COVID-19 quarantine facility.jpg|thumb|The [[Ninoy Aquino Stadium]] in [[Malate, Manila]], reconfigured for use as a quarantine facility.]]\nVarious facilities in the metropolis are being prepared as quarantine sites for less serious COVID-19 cases. Among these are the [[Philippine International Convention Center]], the [[Rizal Memorial Sports Complex]], and the [[World Trade Center Manila|World Trade Center]] will be fully refurbish by April 12. The three facilities alone can accommodate around 2,000 COVID-19 patients. Other non-hospital facilities being considered as possible quarantine sites include the [[PhilSports Complex]], Duty Free Philippines in Para\u00f1aque, [[Amoranto Stadium]], and the [[Quezon Memorial Circle]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Three COVID-19 quarantine facilities in Metro Manila ready by April 12 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/2/Metro-Manila-quarantine-facility-COVID-19.html |accessdate=April 2, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Local governments ===\n\nOn March 12, the Metro Manila Council reached a consensus to implement city-wide [[curfew]]s from 8{{nbsp}}p.m. to 5{{nbsp}}a.m. the following day to be observed during the enhanced community quarantine, during which only \"essential movements\" for the purchase of essential needs or in cases of emergency are permitted during those hours. Commercial establishments are mandated to suspend operations before the start of the curfew at 8{{nbsp}}p.m.<ref>{{cite news |title=Curfew from 8 p.m. to 5 a.m. to take effect in Metro Manila under COVID-19 quarantine |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/metro-manila-quarantine-curfew |accessdate=March 14, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> All local governments in Metro Manila have signed into effect ordinances to implement the curfew. The governments of [[Las Pi\u00f1as]],<ref name=\"Las Pi\u00f1as 24-hr\">{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/las-pinas-city-imposes-24-hour-curfew/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Muntinlupa]],<ref name=\"Munti 24-hr\">{{cite news |title=Muntinlupa placed under 24-hour curfew |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/21/muntinlupa-under-24-hour-curfew.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> [[Navotas]],<ref name=\"Navotas 24-hr\">{{cite news |last1=Calalo |first1=Arlie |title=Navotas imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/03/23/news/top-stories/navotas-imposes-24-hour-curfew/705072/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> and [[Para\u00f1aque]],<ref name=\"Para\u00f1aque 24-hr\">{{cite news |title=Para\u00f1aque imposes 24-hour curfew |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/23/20/paraaque-imposes-24-hour-curfew |accessdate=March 27, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> however, have since issued ordinances extending the implementation of the curfew to a full 24 hours. \n\nOn April 2, {{abbr|IATF-EID|Inter-Agency Task Force on Emerging Infectious Diseases}} chairman and Cabinet Secretary [[Karlo Nograles]] urged the local governments of Luzon to require residents to wear [[Surgical mask|face mask]]s, [[face shield]]s, or any improvised alternatives while out in public for the duration of the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cabico |first1=Gaea Katreena |title=Luzon residents now required to wear face masks outside during lockdown |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/04/02/2005014/luzon-residents-now-required-wear-face-masks-outside-during-lockdown |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> In response, the mayors of [[Malabon]], [[Mandaluyong]],<ref>{{cite news |last1=Casinas |first1=Jhon Aldrin |title=Mandaluyong imposes fine and imprisonment to violators of face mask ordinance |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/09/mandaluyong-imposes-fine-and-imprisonment-to-violators-of-face-mask-ordinance/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> Muntinlupa,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hicap |first1=Jonathan |title=Muntinlupa makes wearing of face masks mandatory |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/02/muntinlupa-makes-wearing-of-face-masks-mandatory/ |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref> Para\u00f1aque,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Para\u00f1aque city residents to always wear face masks when in public places, says mayor |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/04/07/paranaque-city-residents-to-always-wear-face-masks-when-in-public-places-says-mayor/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> [[Pasay]], [[Quezon City]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Wearing of face masks now mandatory in Quezon City |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/4/7/Quezon-City-face-mask-order-COVID.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=April 7, 2020}}</ref> and [[Valenzuela, Metro Manila|Valenzuela]], each issued ordinances to implement the measure within their respective jurisdictions.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Agoncillo |first1=Jodee |last2=Ramos |first2=Mariejo |title=Masks now required in Malabon, Valenzuela, QC, Pasay |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1256010/masks-now-a-must-in-malabon-valenzuela-qc-pasay |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=April 9, 2020}}</ref> \n\n==== Caloocan ====\n\n[[Caloocan]] Mayor [[Oscar Malapitan]] announced on March 10 the suspension of several scheduled events in the city: the Miss Caloocan Pageant, Mega Job Fairs, City Development Council General Assembly, Outstanding Citizens Awards Night, and Family Day activities, to prevent the spread of the virus among large crowds.<ref name=\"Caloocan, Valenzuela\">{{cite news |last1=Caybyab |first1=Marc Jayson |title=Caloocan, Valenzuela cancel events over COVID-19 |url=https://www.philstar.com/nation/2020/03/10/1999490/caloocan-valenzuela-cancel-events-over-covid-19 |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> On March 24, the city announced that it would impose window hours on residents for the purchase of essential goods. Residents could only access the city's [[Palengke|public markets]] between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 9{{nbsp}}a.m. and 4{{nbsp}}p.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m., while supermarkets, banks, and pharmacies can only be accessed between 6{{nbsp}}a.m. to 7{{nbsp}}p.m. The city would also issue quarantine passes, permitting only one resident per household between the ages of 18 to 60 years old to leave their house solely for purchasing such goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Marquez |first1=Consuelo |title=Caloocan gov\u2019t imposes window hours for buying basic goods |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247566/caloocan-govt-imposes-window-hours-for-buying-basic-goods |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Las Pi\u00f1as ====\n\nLas Pi\u00f1as Mayor Imelda Aguilar declared a state of calamity in the city on March 14 after a resident was confirmed to have tested positive for COVID-19,<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as declares state of calamity amid coronavirus alarm |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/14/20/las-pias-declares-state-of-calamity-amid-coronavirus-alarm |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> and on March 21, the Las Pi\u00f1as government began implementing a 24-hour curfew on its residents.<ref name=\"Las Pi\u00f1as 24-hr\"/> Aguilar has urged lessors to extend rental fees on commercial establishments for at least a month,<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fernando |first1=Jean |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City mayor asks commercial establishments to waive rental fees for a month |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/21/las-pinas-city-mayor-asks-commercial-establishments-to-waive-rental-fees-for-a-month/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref> and also warned suppliers, retailers, and store owners against profiteering from the crisis by overpricing or hoarding essential goods.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Ramos |first1=Christa Marie |title=Las Pi\u00f1as City warns vs hoarding, profiteering amid coronavirus quarantine |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1249301/las-pinas-city-warns-vs-hoarding-profiteering-amid-coronavirus-quarantine |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 2, the Las Pi\u00f1as government reports that more than 75,000 food packages have been distributed to the city's households. Mayor Aguilar urged residents who have yet to receive their packages to contact their ''barangay'' hall.<ref>{{cite news |title=Las Pi\u00f1as assures more food packs coming, appeals for patience |url=https://manilastandard.net/lgu/ncr/321147/las-pi-as-assures-more-food-packs-coming-appeals-for-patience.html |accessdate=April 9, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=April 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Las Pi\u00f1as government has announced plans to convert a 100-bed drug rehabilitation center in the city into an [[Isolation (health care)|isolation facility]] for its residents suspected or confirmed to have COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Arcilla |first1=Jan |title=Las Pi\u00f1as to convert drug rehab center as isolation area |url=https://www.manilatimes.net/2020/04/03/news/latest-stories/las-pinas-to-convert-drug-rehab-center-as-isolation-area/709283/ |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=The Manila Times |date=April 3, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Makati ====\n\nIn response to the confirmation of residents of the [[Rockwell Center]] contracting COVID-19, [[Makati]] Mayor [[Abigail Binay]] placed the city under a state of calamity on March 15.<ref name=\"state of calamity\"/> Binay also assured city hall employees that they would continue to receive their salaries amid the enhanced community quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |title=Makati gov't employees, contract workers to get paid during lockdown |url=https://www.rappler.com/nation/255354-makati-govt-employees-salaries-lockdown-coronavirus |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Rappler |date=March 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Makati government launched free shuttle bus services for doctors, nurses, and other employees of the Ospital ng Makati, which runs between the hospital and certain points in the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati gov't deploys buses for OsMak, city hall employees |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1243764/makati-govt-deploys-buses-for-osmak-city-hall-employees |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref> In addition, Mayor Binay announced that tricycle drivers affected by the moratorium would receive an initial {{Philippine peso|2,000|link=yes}} (US$39.23) financial assistance to cover the first two weeks of the quarantine. Binay added that a similar financial compensation would be given to jeepney drivers of the city.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Gonzales |first1=Cathrine |title=Makati to give P2,000-financial aid to city's tricycle drivers |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1244295/makati-to-give-p2000-to-citys-tricycle-drivers-as-financial-aid |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> That same day, the Makati government also announced plans to purchase 5,000 COVID-19 test kits from the [[National Institutes of Health (Philippines)|National Institutes of Health]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zurbano |first1=Joel |title=Makati to procure 5k coronavirus test kits |url=https://manilastandard.net/mobile/article/319887 |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=Manila Standard |date=March 17, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Makati Friendship Suites on March 25 was converted into an isolation facility by the city government to accommodate at most 100 patients suspected of COVID-19 and is equipped with [[x-ray machine]]s, [[defibrillator]]s, and [[cardiac monitor]]s.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Layug |first1=Margaret Claire |title=Makati converts hotel into isolation facility for COVID-19 PUIs |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/metro/731239/makati-converts-hotel-into-isolation-facility-for-covid-19-puis/story/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=GMA News Online |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe Makati government announced on March 28 that [[single parent]]s in the city \"affected by the enhanced community quarantine\" would receive a one-time financial assistance of {{Philippine peso|1,000}} ($19.81) each. Mayor Binay also announced that public school students, persons with disabilities, and senior citizens would also receive financial assistance from the government.<ref>{{cite news |title=Makati gives cash aid to solo parents amid Luzon lockdown |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/28/20/makati-gives-cash-aid-to-solo-parents-amid-luzon-lockdown |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Malabon ====\n\nOn March 18, Malabon Mayor [[Antolin Oreta]] ordered the city government to provide {{Philippine peso|520,000}} ($10,252.26) to each ''barangay'' for the provision of food during the Luzon-wide enhanced community quarantine. Oreta also ordered the provision of {{Philippine peso|6 million}} ($118,156.44) to the city's ''carinderia'' (food stall) owners for them to provide meals for 300 people every day for 15 days.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon City gov\u2019t releases food budget to barangays for needy residents |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-city-govt-releases-food-budget-to-barangays-for-needy-residents/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref> That same day, he called on [[Maynilad Water Services]] to divert the unused [[Water supply and sanitation in the Philippines|water supply]] of closed malls and other commercial establishments to residential areas.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Pedrajas |first1=Joseph Almer |title=Malabon mayor asks water concessionaires to divert mall water supply to residential areas amid COVID-19 threat |url=https://news.mb.com.ph/2020/03/18/malabon-mayor-asks-water-concessionaires-to-divert-mall-water-supply-to-residential-areas-amid-covid-19-threat/ |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Manila Bulletin |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Oreta endorsed all households in Malabon to the social amelioration program of the [[Department of Social Welfare and Development]] (DSWD) mandated in the [[Bayanihan to Heal as One Act]], saying that \"COVID-19 spares no one, rich or poor.\" The DSWD had allotted packages for only 44,032 households in the city, but the [[Philippine Statistics Authority]] reported in 2015 that 86,000 households comprise the population of Malabon.<ref>{{cite news |title='Rich and poor': Malabon mayor to endorse all families to DSWD for aid |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/04/02/20/rich-and-poor-malabon-mayor-to-endorse-all-families-to-dswd-for-aid |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=April 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Mandaluyong ====\n\nThe [[Mandaluyong]] city council passed an ordinance on March 16 declaring the city under a state of calamity, after reporting three COVID-19 patients, six persons under investigation, and 125 persons under monitoring in the city.<ref name=\"Mandaluyong 1st case\"/>\n\nOn March 17, Mandaluyong Mayor [[Carmelita Abalos]] ordered the release of the [[thirteenth salary]] pay to all of the city's government employees.<ref name=\"13th-month pay\">{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong, Manila gov't employees to get early 13th-month, midyear pay during community quarantine |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/17/mandaluyong-city-hall-13th-month.html |accessdate=March 21, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor Abalos stated that around 100,000 bags of relief goods would be distributed [[door-to-door]] to households in Mandaluyong.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mandaluyong to deliver food aid for COVID-19 lockdown \u2018door-to-door\u2019 by weekend |url=https://news.abs-cbn.com/news/03/18/20/mandaluyong-to-deliver-food-aid-for-covid-19-lockdown-door-to-door-by-weekend |accessdate=April 10, 2020 |work=ABS-CBN News |date=March 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==== Manila ====\n\n<center>\n{{Graph:Chart\n|type=line\n